<html>

<title>Gary Bauer's March, 1996 Letter</title>

<body>

<center><h2>A Message From Gary L. Bauer</h2></center>

<p><hr width=75% height=2><p>

March 8, 1996

<p>

Dear Friend:

<p>

Washington is even more hectic than usual these days and the
Family Research Council (FRC) seems to be working 24 hours a day.
While Alaska, Louisiana and Iowa held caucuses in February,
March is the big month for primaries in this presidential year as 
voters in state after state determine whom they will vote for. 
South Carolina led off on March 2.  Twelve more states vote between 
March 5 and 7.  &quot;Super Tuesday&quot; -- which isn't that 
super anymore because so many states have moved up
the date their primary -- follows on March 12.  California votes
at the end of the month.

<p>

By the end of this month, if not sooner, we may know
the name of the Republican presidential nominee.  On the Democratic
side, President Bill Clinton is unopposed and his renomination is 
virtually assured.  Third party candidates like Ross Perot and Jesse 
Jackson may still emerge.

<p>

In all of my contacts with friends of the Family Research Council,
no question is asked me more often than this one:  &quot;Gary,
which candidate for the White House will keep his word and do
the most for families?&quot;  I wish I could answer that question.
But, as I've often mentioned in my letters to you, endorsements
aren't -- and cannot be -- the business of FRC. 
The authors of our tax laws have prohibited nonprofit groups
like FRC from participating in or attempting to influence the
outcome of any election.

<p>

Even more importantly though, our mission is education, and our
goal is the promotion and protection of the traditional family.
Our message is profoundly conservative, but we believe that this
message is both the heritage and the hope of all Americans.  FRC
is in a unique position to bridge the purely partisan conflicts
of our time and to offer a vision of enduring values that any
person of goodwill can embrace.

<p>

But even though I can't tell you whom to vote for, I can talk
to you candidly about issues that I know concern you deeply.
(Our role is to keep pro-family issues at center stage.)  What
has this still-young election year already told us about what's
on the hearts of the American people?

<p>

The answer, I believe, is both worrisome and uplifting.  The
worrisome side is simple.  Voter turnout has been mixed -- lower 
than expected in Iowa, near-record levels in New Hampshire.
Last November, Family Research Council conducted a nationwide
poll which confirmed the fact that a large majority of Americans
believe this nation is on the wrong track, and that the primary
reason for the decline is moral decay.  If Americans are dispirited
about the future and stay away from the polls, the problems we
face will be even more difficult to solve.

<p>

The uplifting part of the answer is that many Americans aren't
dispirited, and they are exercising their rights of citizenship in search 
of change. To better understand what those voters are saying, first we 
must understand what the politicians are saying.  Let's start with
President Bill Clinton's State of the Union address on January 23.

<p>

Remember what was going on back in 1992?  For much of that year,
&quot;family values&quot; took it on the chin from the major media.
Vice President Dan Quayle took aim at Murphy Brown, the fictional
TV heroine, over her deliberate decision to conceive a child out
of wedlock.   Quayle endured a hail of scorn, from Hollywood to
the halls of Congress.  The Vice President was charged with everything
from making too much of a TV show to trying to &quot;divide the
nation.&quot;  All of this happened merely because he suggested
that America's culture shouldn't encourage family break-up and
promiscuity.

<p>

But the attack on family values didn't stop there.  After the
1992 presidential election, pundits both inside and outside the
GOP made &quot;family values&quot; the scapegoat for the defeat
of President George Bush.  The GOP platform, with its clear statements
on abortion and homosexuality, was the cause, these writers said,
of the first Democratic presidential victory in 16 years.  This
analysis was ludicrous, but it became the accepted wisdom.  George
Bush lost for a number of reasons, including running a poorly
strategized campaign and breaking his promise of &quot;no new taxes.&quot;

<p>

Now lets flash forward.  Before a crowded House chamber and a
national television office just five weeks ago, Bill Clinton made
a speech that had cultural values as its primary theme.  He talked
with feeling about welfare reform, getting tough on drugs, reducing
teen pregnancy, and jawboning Hollywood directors into taming
violence on television.  This time, the pundits were silent. 
The next day, The <i>New York Times</i> merely noted that 
Clinton's &quot;values talk&quot; had wide public support.

<p>

In this atmosphere, the Republican presidential race has likewise
gone forward with a sharpened focus on family issues -- and those
issues seem to be boosting the candidates who express them most clearly. 
The sanctity of human life is a major example. Much of official 
Washington believes that abortion and euthanasia are just the kind of 
&quot;divisive&quot; issues that doom politicians to the margins
of public life.  But advocates of the right to life have played a 
major role in the primaries to date. Liberal pundits overlook the 
fact that the two most ardent champions of legal abortion in the 
race -- Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and Gov. Pete Wilson of 
California -- dropped out months ago for lack of public support.

<p>

Defending the right to life is one way to stand up for &quot;the
little guy.&quot;  A similar sentiment may be driving the voter
response to candidates who speak to the average family's economic 
insecurity.   The families who read my letters regularly understand 
this insecurity very well.  Their tax burden has soared in the past
generation.  In many cases, economic pressures have forced both
Mom and Dad to work.  Too many families are living from paycheck
to paycheck.  If the economy turns down or wages continue to stagnate,
what will these families do?

<p>

On top of this is the indifference of so many in government -- and
others on Wall Street who seem to think globally while ignoring
things that matter here at home.  Americans sense that the strong
ties of loyalty and community which have always bound us together
are fraying.  Major companies close factories here and open new
ones overseas, where labor costs are drastically lower.  American
workers who have lost their jobs are told by some conservative
leaders that what's happened to them is just a &quot;structural
adjustment.&quot;  &quot;Don't worry,&quot; they're advised, the
U.S. economy will be the healthier for it 10 years down the road.
I can still vividly remember my own father, sitting at our kitchen
table in despair after he lost his job.  Every family worries
whether such a scene will be played out in their own kitchen.
Some leading liberals counter that the answer to the problem
is retraining, or &quot;lifelong learning,&quot; a response that
seems a little glib to working men and women worried about mouths
to feed today and tomorrow.

<p>

Underlying all of this is a sense that something has changed
in America.  America's families have shouldered the burdens of
World War II, Vietnam and the Cold War.  They have borne each
cross bravely, run the race, and won the crown -- but still their
government will not let up and allow them to keep a little more
of what they earn.  America's families built the world's greatest
peacetime economy, shared their resources to rebuild post war
Europe, even assisted Japan in making the transition to a modern
industrial democracy.  They have founded global institutions to
keep the peace, and risked nuclear holocaust to resist the nightmare
of communism.  For all their pains, they have been rewarded with
political leaders in both parties who tell them they are selfish
because they want to keep American jobs on American soil.

<p>

&quot;You must be patient,&quot; these leaders say -- all the while
committing vast amounts of our hard-earned tax money to programs
that do not work, to bureaucrats who delight in interfering with the 
religious rights of the people, to artworks that scorn the values of
the people who foot the bills, and to lavish retirement programs
for a class of permanent legislators who have abandoned the ideals
of Madison and Jefferson.

<p>

Today, barely 10 weeks into this election year, the voices of
the forgotten Americans are being heard.  On issue after issue -- tax
reform, parental choice in education, control of illegal immigration,
campaign finance reform, term limits, support for the institution
of marriage, sanctity of life -- voters are gravitating toward candidates
who are saying that <b>values do matter</b> and that power and resources
must begin flowing away from Washington and back toward families
and local communities.

<p>

That same message was at the core of the 1994 congressional elections.
It may be one reason why a record number of longtime incumbents
are retiring from the House and Senate this year.  It's rare that
anyone in Washington voluntarily gives up the reins of power.
But in one sense, that is what is being asked of every politician
in the nation's capital.

<p>

Our welfare system is destroying families? Then return power
to the states to innovate and enlist more aid from private charities
to combat poverty.  Academic achievement continues to decline?
Then return authority and resources to local school districts.
Economic growth is faltering?  Then lift the burden of tax and
regulation that is stifling entrepreneurs.

<p>

It's no accident that these are the concerns defining political
trends in this election year. They are the same concerns that fill the 
letters I receive every day from friends of FRC. 
What ties so many of these issues together is concern for our children's 
future.  We inherited a nation that was free. We were a nation where a 
man's word was his bond.  We were a nation where a person trying to start 
a business was hailed as a pioneer, not hauled before a dozen permit boards 
like a suspected criminal.  We were a nation where parents could let their 
children spend an afternoon watching a double feature at the local theater
without fearing they would be saturated with sex and violence
on the screen.  We were a nation where the &quot;village&quot;
did, to borrow Hillary Clinton's word, help raise children, but
always with respect for parental authority.

<p>

That nation had its deep flaws -- racial prejudice, for one.  But
to that problem we have now added others.  We have kept the bathwater 
and (all too literally!) thrown out the baby.

<p>

FRC believes that the national public policy debate is too important
for families to sit on the sidelines.  We will continue to put
ideas and research on the table that will chase the ghosts of
relativism from our public life.  We will continue to insist that
some values are good for families, while others are bad. We will continue 
to fight for the causes that endure:  respect for every human life, the
honorable bonds of husband and wife, the virtue of sexual restraint,
the daily love that only a parent can lavish on a child.

<p>

These are the themes that guide FRC.  I wish I had enough space here 
to tell you of all the activities in which our government relations and 
policy staff are now engaged.  Be sure to read the latest <i>Washington 
Watch</i> for all the details -- weekly updates are available
from our legislative hotline at 202-783-HOME.  And don't forget
to consult the enclosed reply card for information on the latest FRC 
resources.

<p>

Thank you for your prayers, your encouragement and your financial
support.  Your partnership with us is essential to our success.
Slowly but surely, this great nation is awakening to the dream
of restoring its families and communities.  God bless you for
all you're doing to help turn this dream into a reality.

<p>

Sincerely,

<p><br>

Gary L. Bauer<br>
President

<p>

P.S.  Our hope that millions of Americans will learn more about
the pro-family agenda is coming true.  The response to my book,
<i>Our Hopes, Our Dreams</i>, has been excellent, but the best
news is that we are reaching a wide secular audience as well.
Two major book chains, Walden Books and B. Dalton, are now carrying
it!  I've just received word that <i>Publisher's Weekly</i>, one
of the major resources that booksellers and librarians use to
determine what books they will acquire, will carry a review of
the book.  Thank you for your prayers and for all you're doing
to help get this resource in the hands of people who are considering
and embracing our issues! Let's keep the momentum going!

<p><hr width=60%><p>

<center>

<font size=-1>

