    <tr>
      <td height=2></td>
      <td colspan=6></td>
      <td width=420 height=48 colspan=4 rowspan=2 valign=top align=left>

<p align=center><center><B><font face="Arial" size=5>Accounting Department</center></p></B></font>


      </td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=46></td>
      <td width=102 height=707 colspan=4 rowspan=3 valign=top align=left>
        <map name="map807">
          <area shape="rect" coords="29,628,65,670" href="page33.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="21,45,80,97" href="index.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="26,293,75,331" href="page5.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="32,137,69,178" href="page3.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="30,543,71,592" href="page18.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="24,371,77,417" href="page6.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="25,218,76,253" href="page4.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="33,457,68,503" href="page8.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,97,101,130" href="index.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,178,101,211" href="page3.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,253,101,286" href="page4.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,331,101,364" href="page5.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,417,101,450" href="page6.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,503,101,536" href="page8.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,592,101,625" href="page18.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,674,101,707" href="page33.html">
        </map>
        <img width=103 height=708 border=0 src="img85.gif" usemap="#map807">
      </td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=12></td>
      <td colspan=8></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=649></td>
      <td></td>
      <td width=426 height=810 colspan=4 rowspan=6 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=418></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=802></td>
            <td width=418 height=802 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Accounting has been called the &quot;language of business.&quot; The concepts and terms of accounting are used to describe and measure the events of daily business activity. The accountant measures, aggregates, and reports financial information necessary for decision-making by organizational managers, owners, investors, government agencies, and other users. Timely and accurate information on operations is crucial to success in today&#39;s rapidly changing business environment and the accountant is the one responsible for this critical business function.&nbsp; The importance of accounting information to business opens many career opportunities for accountants. The opportunities generally are in-- </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Public Accounting - Public accountants provide consulting services to organizations and individuals. A critical function they perform is the preparation and certification for accuracy of financial reports used by individuals outside of the firm such as investors or government agencies., Those following a career in this area will generally seek to become certified public accountants (CPA&#39;s). </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Private Accounting - Private accountants are employed by businesses of all types and sizes. They develop accounting reports used by the firm&#39;s management for internal decision making as well as prepare reports for external users. Because of the importance of accurate information to decision makers, a firms&#39; internal accountants are often important members of its management team. Many following this career will seek to become certified managerial accountants (CMA). </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Government Accounting - Accounting for government agencies and other not-for-profit organizations requires special methods and reporting procedures not used in profit-oriented firms. Governmental Accountants perform similar functions as do private accountants for local, state, and federal agencies and charitable organizations. </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>ACCOUNTING PROGRAM<br>
All business students at Idaho State receive a solid foundation in general education and understanding of general business practices. At least half of the courses taken for a bachelor of business administration degree are in the liberal arts and sciences. A thorough understanding of general business operations is gained through the business core requirements. Accounting majors may then choose from two program tracks-one designed specifically for those seeking a career in public accounting and a second track for those planning careers in private or governmental accounting. Students may shape their programs to meet their individual interests and career plans by choosing electives from the following areas: <br>
</p><p align=center><center></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>Managerial Tax Planning<br>
Business and Fiduciary Taxation</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2><br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>Auditing<br>
Advanced Managerial Cost Accounting<br>
Accounting Theory<br>
Governmental Accounting<br>
Comparative International Accounting</center></p></font>
            </td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=4></td>
            <td colspan=2>The <A HREF="HNDBK.HTM">Accounting Student Handbook</a> contains additional information about the accounting program including suggested schedules, and course lists.<P>

<P>You may also visit the <A HREF="/scripts/studenturl.idc?DEP=Accounting">Accounting student home pages</A>
or the <A HREF="/classes/accounting/">Accounting course syllabi</a>.<br><br>

</td>
          </tr>
        </table>

