      <td colspan=6></td>
      <td width=420 height=48 colspan=4 rowspan=2 valign=top align=left>

<p align=center><center><B><font face="Arial" size=5>Marketing Department</center></p></B></font>


      </td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=46></td>
      <td width=102 height=707 colspan=4 rowspan=3 valign=top align=left>
        <map name="map1674">
          <area shape="rect" coords="29,628,65,670" href="page33.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="21,45,80,97" href="index.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="26,293,75,331" href="page5.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="32,137,69,178" href="page3.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="30,543,71,592" href="page18.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="24,371,77,417" href="page6.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="25,218,76,253" href="page4.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="33,457,68,503" href="page8.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,97,101,130" href="index.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,178,101,211" href="page3.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,253,101,286" href="page4.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,331,101,364" href="page5.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,417,101,450" href="page6.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,503,101,536" href="page8.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,592,101,625" href="page18.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="1,674,101,707" href="page33.html">
        </map>
        <img width=103 height=708 border=0 src="img101.gif" usemap="#map1674">
      </td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=12></td>
      <td colspan=8></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=649></td>
      <td></td>
      <td width=426 height=810 colspan=4 rowspan=6 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=418></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=802></td>
            <td width=418 height=802 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>The goal of the Department of Marketing at ISU&#39;s College of Business is to meet the needs of students interested in marketing as a career and the needs of local, national, and international organizations which hire our graduates. Marketing managers are concerned with finding out what consumers want and providing products that meet consumer&#39;s needs, wants, and desires. The backbone of business&#39; marketing effort is sales, and that is where the largest need for our graduates is, and where our educational emphasis lies.&nbsp; Careers include:<br><br>
<B>Personal Selling </B>&nbsp;
Personal Selling is the key component of our marketing program. We are proud to be one of the leading universities specializing in this field. ISU prepares graduates for careers that can take them into the worlds of industrial, wholesale, or retail sales on a regional, national, or global scale and beyond to other aspects of marketing management. </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>In addition to sales management, our graduate marketing professionals are familiar with the following areas: </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><B><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Market Research-</B> The analysis of market potential for new products or the expansion of sales of existing products. This field might include (1) market analysis, (2) site selection, (3) consumer research, (4) advertising research and analysis, (5) operations research, and (6) sales analysis and forecasting. <br>
<B>Marketing Management</B>&nbsp; The design of products, packaging, promotion and pricing to match consumer needs, wants, and demand. <br>
<B>Advertising and Promotion&nbsp; </B>are those parts of the distribution channel that works between the manufacturer and the retailer and between the retailer and consumer. <br>
<B>Distribution </B>is the assurance that the right products are where the need to be when the need to be there, while maintaining control over costs. <br>
</p><p align=left></font><B><font face="Arial" size=4>Marketing Program<br>
</p><p align=left></B></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>The Bachelor of Business Administration degree with a major in Marketing includes a solid general education. Half of the courses taken for a BBA are from the arts and sciences. Core requirements of the College of Business provide an opportunity to become familiar with accounting, computer information systems, business statistics, the legal environment of organizations, individual and organizational behavior, operations/production management, international business and financial markets, corporate financial management, and business communications. </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1><br>
<br>
</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>In addition to the required courses in Marketing Analysis, Personal Selling, Sales Management and Advanced Marketing Management, marketing majors may select from a number of&nbsp; electives to shape their programs to meet their individual interests and career goals. Electives include courses in: <br>
</p><p align=center><center></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>Marketing Communication <br>
Purchasing <br>
Retailing Management <br>
Marketing Channels <br>
Logistics <br>
International Marketing <br>
Managerial Cost Accounting</center></p></font>

<br><br>
Please visit the <a href="/classes/marketing">Marketing course syllabi</a> or the <a href="/scripts/studenturl.idc?DEP=Marketing">Marketing student home pages</a>.<br><br>
            </td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
