    <tr>
      <td height=649></td>
      <td></td>
      <td width=426 height=810 colspan=4 rowspan=6 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=418></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=802></td>
            <td width=418 height=802 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Timely, accurate and pertinent information is critical to managers as they meet decision making needs of the competitive business environment. Rapidly changing computer technology, both in hardware and software design, is providing the capability for businesses and other organizations to develop complex information systems to meet growing business information needs. <br>
<br>
The computer information systems program is designed specifically to prepare students to design and manage computer based information systems. Combining concepts of computer science, computer hardware design, software engineering, and management, the program provides an in-depth understanding of the analysis and design of computer based management systems and the management of the information resource. The program intends to acquaint the students with the design and management of information systems ranging from those using small desk-top or personal computers to large mainframe systems. <br>
<br>
C</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>OLLEGE OF </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>B</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>USINESS </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>C</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>OMPUTER </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>R</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>ESOURCES </font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2><br>
The College of Business has two HP-9000, three Sun sytems with work stations, Five Windows NT servers, a network laboratory, and several small systems.<br>
<br>
COMPUTER INFORMATION SYSTEMS PROGRAM<br>
All business students at Idaho State University receive a solid foundation in general education needed to be successful in any field. Half of the courses taken for a bachelor of business administration degree are from the liberal arts and sciences. A broad base understanding of business is gained from the business core requirements. Computer Information Systems majors will then take a common set of CIS courses designed to give them a thorough understanding of computer programming, management information systems, and systems analysis. Students may shape their programs to meet their individual interests and career objectives by taking elective courses in the areas of: <br>
<br>
Quantitative Methods <br>
Computer Languages <br>
Decision Support Systems <br>
Expert Systems in Business <br>
Network and Communication Systems <br>
Business Systems Simulation <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<a href="/classes/cis/index.html">Computer Information Systems Syallabi</a><br>
<br>
<a href="/scripts/studenturl.idc?DEP=Computer_Information_Systems">Computer Information Systems Students</A> <br>
<br>
</p></font>
            </td>
            <td></td>
