    <tr>
      <td height=649></td>
      <td></td>
      <td width=426 height=810 colspan=4 rowspan=6 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=418></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=802></td>
            <td width=418 height=802 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Financial Managers specialize in the analysis of risk and potential returns from alternative uses of a business firm&#39;s or individual&#39;s resources. The finance major should have a broad understanding of business management concepts accompanied by a sound background in economic theory, management information systems, and quantitative techniques. The nature of the work also requires that financial managers possess effective communication skills, a basic understanding of accounting and financial procedures, and the ability to work well with people in all other parts of the organization. <br>
</p><p align=left></font><B><font face="Arial" size=4>Corporate Financial Office <br>
</p><p align=left></B></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>In business organizations, the proper management of the firm&#39;s financial resources may be the difference between profit and loss. Financial officers have the responsibility for overseeing this important function for the firm. <br>
</p><p align=left></font><B><font face="Arial" size=4>Financial Institutions <br>
</p><p align=left></B></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Officers of banks, credit unions, savings and loans, and other financial institutions manage the institution&#39;s resources and advise customers on individual financial investments. <br>
</p><p align=left></font><B><font face="Arial" size=4>Investment Advising/Brokerage <br>
</p><p align=left></B></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Investment advisors/brokers advise individuals and organizations on their investments. They may also manage investments for individual clients or mutual funds. <br>
</p><p align=left></font><B><font face="Arial" size=4>Real Estate <br>
</p><p align=left></B></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Financial analysts appraise, market, and manage land, buildings, and other real property for maximum return to the real estate owner and investor. <br>
<br>
</p><p align=left></font><B><font face="Arial" size=5>ISU&#39;s Finance Department<br>
</p><p align=left></B></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>
All business students receive the sound foundation of general education courses needed for success in any field. These are followed by a broad understanding of business principles gained from the business core curriculum. Finance majors then take common finance requirements in corporate financial management and investments. Students may shape their programs to meet their individual interests and career goals by taking electives in these areas: <br>
<br>
</p><p align=center><center>Corporate Financial Management<br>
Real Estate Finance and Property Appraisal<br>
Financial Management of Depository Institutions<br>
Risk Management and Insurance<br>
International Finance<br>
Managerial Cost Accounting</center></p></font>

<br><br>
Please visit the <a href="/classes/Finance">Finance course syllabi</a> or the <a href="/scripts/studenturl.idc?DEP=Finance">Finance student home pages</a>.<br><br>
            </td>
