    <tr>
      <td height=649></td>
      <td></td>
      <td width=426 height=810 colspan=4 rowspan=6 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=418></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=802></td>
            <td width=418 height=802 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Management is the science and art of accomplishing organizational objectives through planning, organizing, directing and controlling human, fiscal, and physical resources. A degree in management prepares a student for a variety of challenging careers. Graduates in management are employed in all sectors of business, government, and not-for-profit organizations. Job titles held by management graduates include: <br>
</p><p align=center><center></font><font face="Times New Roman" size=1>Personnel Director/Officer<br>
OSHA Managers<br>
Bank Officer<br>
Pension and Benefits Administrator<br>
Inventory Manager<br>
Maintenance Manager<br>
Production Cost Analyst<br>
Production Planner<br>
Management Trainee<br>
Restaurant Manager<br>
Retail Store Manager</font><font face="Times New Roman" size=2><br>
</center></p><p align=left><br>
The different kinds of jobs managers must do and the kinds of knowledge they must have fall into several broad categories. <br>
<br>
Problem Solving-the recognition of problems, developing and analyzing possible solutions, and implementing selected solutions. Human Relations-motivation, communications, and development of effective relations with people both in and outside the organization. <br>
<br>
Organizational Skill-planning and implementing actions to achieve various goals of the organization. This includes knowledge of labor relations and personnel processes, production management, and operations procedures. <br>
<br>
MANAGEMENT PROGRAM<br>
All business students at Idaho State University receive a solid foundation in general education requirements. Half of all courses taken for a bachelor of business administration degree in management are from the liberal arts and sciences. A broad-based understanding of business operations is gained through the business core requirements. Management majors follow the general business core with advanced courses in organizational behavior and human resources management. A student may then select: <br>
<br>
<B>An Emphasis in Human Resources/Industrial Relations</B> which prepares a student to work with the personnel or labor relations functions within a business:<br>
<br>
<B>An Emphasis in Productions/Operations Management</B> which prepares a student to manage the manufacturing or processing of raw materials into finished goods or services; OR <br>
<br>
<B>No Emphasis</B> Students would choose electives from the areas of business law, personnel management, labor law and relations, production management, international business or organizational theory to meet their individual interests and career goals.</p></font>

<br><br>
Please visit the <a href="/classes/Management">Management course syllabi</a> or the <a href="/scripts/studenturl.idc?DEP=Management">Management student home pages</a>.<br><br>
            </td>
            <td></td>
