Accept-Ranges: bytes
Last-Modified: Mon, 14 Oct 1996 20:59:30 GMT
Content-Length: 3871
</DOCHDR>
<!doctype html public "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<meta name="Generator" content="Microsoft Publisher 97">
<title>CobWeb</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#009966" vlink="#663399" text="#000000" >
<a name=Page15></a>
  
  <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
    <tr>
      <td width=9 height=7></td>
      <td width=555></td>
      <td width=2></td>
      <td width=10></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=47></td>
      <td width=555 height=47 colspan=1 rowspan=1 valign=top align=left>
        <map name="map1404">
          <area shape="rect" coords="15,25,39,38" href="page8.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="9,17,39,47" href="page8.html">
        </map>
        <img width=554 height=48 border=0 src="img75.gif" usemap="#map1404">
      </td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=870></td>
      <td width=557 height=870 colspan=2 rowspan=1 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=549></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=862></td>
            <td width=549 height=862 valign=top align=left>

<p align=center><center><B><font face="Times New Roman" size=3>New Accounting Course Benefits Both Students and Business<br>
</center></p><p align=left><br>
</B>A new community-based learning course provides free consulting to area businesses and a taste of the real world to accounting students. Accounting 470, Contemporary Issues in Management Accounting, is a senior elective in which student teams tackle management accounting projects aimed at addressing problems of concern to local business owners and managers.<br>
<br>
The class was first offered on an experimental basis last spring to four brave students who created an activity-based costing system for a business process within a local medical practice. Based on the results, they recommended a re-engineering of the business process. The sponsor was so pleased with the results he is hosting another team this fall.<br>
<br>
This semester twenty students are immersed in seven projects involved in a variety of activities. Three teams are focusing on developing cost accounting and/or cost management systems, one for a specialty manufacturer in Blackfoot, another for a farming operation in Rupert, and the third for a combined retail/service business in Idaho Falls. Potential start-up companies are the charge of several other teams, with two groups working through the Pocatello Small Business Development Center (SBDC), and another studying the economic feasibility of a spin-off from an existing business. Finally, one team is working on developing a customer-driven performance measurement system for a Pocatello-based industrial service organization.<br>
<br>
Early in the semester, students are introduced to basic consulting conduct.Each student signs a commitment of confidentiality to all sponsor organizations serviced in the course. Teams are coached and guided throughout the term via weekly faculty/team conferences in order to help ensure high quality and timely service.<br>
<br>
Any person or organization interested in sponsoring a student team in the future should contact Professor Priscilla Reis of the accounting department at (208) 236-3638 or reispris@ISU,EDU.</p></font>
            </td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=4></td>
            <td colspan=2></td>
          </tr>
        </table>



      </td>
      <td></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=36></td>
      <td colspan=3></td>
    </tr>
  </table>

</body>
</html>

