      <td height=870></td>
      <td width=557 height=870 colspan=2 rowspan=1 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=549></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=862></td>
            <td width=549 height=862 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=3>In April of this year, Governor Phil Batt appointed Management Professor John Kilpatrick to a task force on Medicaid reform.&nbsp; Because of expected cuts&nbsp; in Medicaid funds at both the federal and state levels, the task force&#39;s goal is to find ways to make the Medicaid program more cost effective while serving the needs of Idaho&#39;s medically indigent.&nbsp; &nbsp; <br>
<br>
Since May, the Council has been involved in the lengthy and complex process of&nbsp; developing a set of recommendations to be delivered to Governor Batt by early December.&nbsp; After going through a crash course on the Medicaid program, council members held&nbsp; 21 public meetings in 7 Idaho cities: Couer d&#39;Alene, Lewiston, Nampa, Boise, Twin Falls, Pocatello and Idaho Falls.&nbsp; These hearings resulted in over 700 specific recommendations from the public, providers, and recipients.&nbsp; &nbsp; <br>
<br>
Next the council met in Boise to develop a formal mission statement and begin organizing the&nbsp; public comments into a coherent set of principles and recommendations.&nbsp; Working in sub-committees, the council came up with a preliminary list of just over 100.&nbsp; In August a draft of these proposals was circulated and another round of public hearings held.&nbsp; When public comment has been summarized and reviewed, the council will meet to revise the proposals further. <br>
<br>
 Because of the complexity of the issues involved, a subcommittee may continue working on the reform until well into the new year.&nbsp; Once the recommendations are submitted to the governor, he and his staff will make decisions as to which ones will be presented to the legislature or passed on to the Idaho Department of Health and Welfare for study and implementation.<br>
<br>
While the process has been arduous and time-consuming, Professor Kilpatrick feels that getting to know the council members from across the state and&nbsp; working with them has been a valuable experience.</p></font>
            </td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
