<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<meta name="Generator" content="Microsoft Publisher 97">
<title>CobWeb</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#009966" vlink="#663399" text="#000000" >
<a name=Page12></a>
  
  <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
    <tr>
      <td width=9 height=7></td>
      <td width=555></td>
      <td width=2></td>
      <td width=10></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=47></td>
      <td width=555 height=47 colspan=1 rowspan=1 valign=top align=left>
        <map name="map1396">
          <area shape="rect" coords="15,25,39,38" href="page8.html">
          <area shape="rect" coords="9,17,39,47" href="page8.html">
        </map>
        <img width=554 height=48 border=0 src="img72.gif" usemap="#map1396">
      </td>
      <td colspan=2></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td height=896></td>
      <td width=557 height=896 colspan=2 rowspan=1 valign=top align=left>
        
        <table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr>
            <td width=4 height=4></td>
            <td width=549></td>
            <td width=4></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=889></td>
            <td width=549 height=889 valign=top align=left>

<p align=left><font face="Times New Roman" size=2>Sabbaticals at ISU are competitively awarded on the basis of past record, current performance, years at ISU, and the merits of the sabbatical proposal. Johnson adds that sabbaticals by definition are meant to be a period of rejuvenation. But hard work and rejuvenation can go hand in hand. &quot;I hope critics of academic sabbaticals come to recognize the merits and importance of sabbaticals. Perhaps one day we will see an increase of sabbaticals in the private sector--this is common practice in some European countries. My sabbatical was a wonderful change--I continued to work hard but came back refreshed, spending my entire summer working hard to progress my sabbatical works to fruition.&quot;<br>
<br>
Currently Johnson is &quot;recovering&quot; from his recent sabbatical; at least he likes to tease that that is what he is doing. He spent most of his spring 1996 sabbatical in the Los Angeles area researching and writing. With his trusty laptop computer in tow, he made frequent trips to UCLA, USC, and CSULA libraries. Although his sabbatical was awarded for the spring semester, he viewed the spring/summer period as his &quot;informal&quot; sabbatical period. (Most professors are not on contract during the summer months although most are professionally active during this period.)<br>
<br>
Johnson worked on a number of research projects during his sabbatical, some of which have already been accepted. He will present three papers at conferences this fall that will be published in the conferences&#39; Proceedings. They are 1) <I>Organizational and Behavioral Constraints to Employment Testing</I> (Institute for Behavioral and Applied Management, Portland, Maine), 2) <I>The EEOC&#39;s Uniform Guidelines on Employee Selection Procedures: Outdated, Misleading, and Counterproductive</I> <I>(</I>American Association of Employment Principles and Practices<I>, </I>San Diego<I>), and 3) Employment Test Validation: Conducting and Documenting The</I> <I>Process (</I>Association Employment Principles and Practices<I>)</I>.<br>
<br>
He has also submitted a manuscript, <I>The Sub-dimension Versus Overall Criterion Debate: Interpreting Test Validation Data,</I> to the Western Decision Science Institute and another paper, <I>The Ethics of Downsizing: The View From Non-managers</I> to <U>The Workplace</U> <U>Journal</U>.<br>
<br>
Johnson is working with fellow faculty members Professors Gamewell Gantt and James Jolly in researching <I>The Legal Status of Validity Generalization for Validating Employment Tests</I>. He has also made significant progress researching a handful of other topics including: <I>The Affirmative Action Versus Employment Testing Tug-A-War: Can Their Differences Be Reconciled?, Misrepresentations and Abuses of Personnel Selection Testing, Behavioral Realities of Conducting Job Analysis and Conducting Test Validation, </I>and <I>Employment Testing, the ADA, and Job Analysis</I>. <br>
<br>
Johnson is in his tenth year as a faculty member and is working as hard as ever. &quot;When I started in this career I knew I was going to have to work hard and long hours to earn tenure and promotions, and I did. I also thought that after reaching the rank of full professor my 60-hour weeks might lessen and I could get away with 40- to 50-hour weeks, at least some of the time. It just hasn&#39;t worked that way. We are working as hard as ever,and I don&#39;t expect that to change. Besides, work is more fun when I am really cranking it out. When I tell my students this, some of them just look at me in amazement.&quot;<br>
<br>
Johnson is enjoying himself while he is teaching his classes and conducting research. His first love is teaching, which is the reason he earned his doctorate degree in the first place. &quot;I had a chance to teach management courses while I was an MBA student at California State University, Los Angeles. I loved it and knew that was what I wanted to do long term.&quot;<br>
<br>
He also keeps busy with his involvement in community and university service. He is the President of the Eastern Idaho Society for Human Resources Managers, which is a professional association for practicing personnel/human resources managers. During past five years, he served this group as a Vice President, Membership Director, and Board member. He was also elected by his fellow College faculty members to serve as one of its two representatives on the Faculty Senate for the next three years. He enjoys signing memos as &quot;Senator Johnson.&quot; John Kilpatrick (Senator Kilpatrick!!) of the Department of Management also serves the College in this capacity.</p></font>
            </td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td height=4></td>
            <td colspan=2></td>
          </tr>
        </table>



      </td>
      <td></td>
    </tr>
