<p><a name="STUDENTHANDBOOK"><b>USING THE STUDENT HANDBOOK</b></a> </p>
<p>The purpose of this handbook is to provide a compact, comprehensive source of information 
on the Idaho State University accounting program. It is intended to help prospective students 
familiarize themselves with the Program and to aid the progress of students currently in 
accounting degree program. The handbook is not the sole source of information on the Idaho 
State University accounting program. In particular, we remind you that students are 
responsible for understanding and complying with the policies described in the Idaho State 
University catalogs. The University and College of Business policies described within the 
catalogs and this handbook are strictly adhered to by the accounting program. </p>
<p>This handbook is intended to aid, but not replace, the advising provided within the accounting 
program. It is not designed to cover unusual circumstances. In planning your specific program 
of studies and for answers to questions not covered in the handbook, we encourage you to 
seek help of your undergraduate or graduate advisor. </p>
<p>We hope that this handbook will be a useful supplement to our counseling in guiding you 
through your degree program. The faculty and staff sincerely wish that the time you spend as 
part of the Idaho State University accounting program will be both enriching and enjoyable. 
This handbook can help in achieving those goals; please read it carefully. </p>
<p><a name="ROLE"><b>ROLE AND MISSION OF THE ACCOUNTING DEPARTMENT</b> </a></p>
<p>The Accounting Department, an integral part of the College of Business, shares the role and 
mission of its College and the University as established by the State Board of Education. Thus, 
the Department responds to current and emerging demands within the state and region and 
primarily serves local and statewide constituencies of students, accountants, and other 
interested parties. </p>
<p>The Department's primary mission is to offer a quality professional education in accounting. As 
such, the Department imparts business and accounting knowledge, develops competencies in 
emerging technologies, fosters learning skills, and promotes the pursuit of life-long learning. 
The Department also strives to enhance communication skills, interpersonal and leadership 
skills, and critical thinking abilities. Ethical awareness, with attendant standards and 
perspectives, is also encouraged. </p>
<p>The research mission of the Department complements and enhances the instructional mission. 
Research activities are conducted to improve the understanding of accounting theory and 
practice among the Department's main constituents. Thus, research and related activities are 
oriented primarily towards the needs of practitioners and students. Consequently, 
departmental research typically focuses upon behavioral aspects of accounting, teaching 
methodologies, emerging accounting issues, and tax legislation. </p>
<p>The service mission also addresses the needs of the Department's constituents. The 
Department seeks to use its expertise to enhance economic development in the region and to 
meet the continuing educational needs of business professionals and accountants. The 
Department encourages participation in and service to professional and community 
organizations. The Department also provides applied research and other assistance when 
needed by various organizations. </p>
