<p><b>Notes:</b> </p>
<ol>
<li>Completion of at least 128 credits is required for graduation. </li>
<li>A minimum of 64 non-business credits must be completed. </li>
<li>Students planning to take the CPA or CMA examinations should plan to continue in the 
MBA-Accounting program upon completion of BBA requirements </li>
<li>Some students may find a faster (or slower) pace more suitable for them. Consult an 
advisor to develop your individualized plan of study. </li>
<li>A &#147;C&#148; grade or higher is required for all accounting major requirements, and students 
may repeat a course in which less than a &#147;C&#148; is earned only once. </li>
</ol>
<p><a name="UNDERGRADUATECOURSEDESCRIPTIONS"><b>UNDERGRADUATE COURSE DESCRIPTIONS</b> </a></p>
<p><b>SOPHOMORE BUSINESS REQUIREMENTS</b> </p>
<p><b>ACCT 201 Principles of Accounting I</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3 </p>
<p>Accounting principles, classification of accounts, books of original entry, preparation of 
financial statements, adjusting entries and closing process, and analysis of major balance sheet 
and income statement items. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 241 Managerial Cost Accounting</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 201, MATH 111 </p>
<p>Accounting of costs relating to production, marketing, and administration of manufacturing 
enterprises. Emphasizes cost information in control, decision making, and long-range planning. </p>
<p><b>MGT 216 Business Statistics</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: MATH 111 </p>
<p>Frequency distributions, measures of central tendency and dispersion, index number, 
probability and normal distributions, sampling methods, time series, trends, cycles, inference, 
simple correlation and regression, and application to business problems. </p>
<p><b>MGT 217 Advanced Business Statistics</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: MGT 216 </p>
<p>Application of statistical techniques with emphasis on the interpretation of computer software 
output in managerial decision making. </p>
<p><b>MGT 261 Legal Environment of Organizations</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3 </p>
<p>Legal environment as it pertains to day-to-day operation of a business. Emphasis on the legal 
aspects of relationships of profit and non-profit organizations, consumers, employees, and 
government agencies. </p>
<p><b>SPEECH 201 Principles of Speech</b> </p>
<p>Credits 2 </p>
<p>Basic course in oral communication that emphasizes the theory and practice of informative 
speaking, logical argumentation, persuasion, small group discussion, and interpersonal 
communication. Designed to explain the humanistic nature of human communication and to 
improve a student's ability to express ideas orally. </p>
<p><a name="UPPERDIVISIONREQUIREMENTS"><b>UPPER DIVISION REQUIREMENTS</b> </a></p>
<p><a name="COLLEGEOFBUSINESSREQUIREMENTS"><b>COLLEGE OF BUSINESS REQUIREMENTS</b> </a></p>
<p><b>ENGL 308 Business Communications</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ENGL 201 and completion of 60 credits </p>
<p>An advanced course in conventions of business communications, emphasizing purpose and 
audience. Focus on style, semantics, research skills, format, persuasion, and critical analysis 
and synthesis of data. </p>
<p><b>CIS 381 Management Information Systems</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 201 </p>
<p>Theory and methodology of the application of information systems to a broad range of 
organizational functions for various management levels. </p>
<p><b>FIN 310 International Business and Financial Markets</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 202 or 241 and ECON 201-202 </p>
<p>Functions/operations, of domestic/international financial markets/institutions, shielding 
corporation cash flows from interest and exchange rate risk. </p>
<p><b>FIN 315 Corporate Financial Management</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 202 or 241 and ECON 201-202 and MATH 120 </p>
<p>Emphasis on the sources of financing and the efficient utilization of funds. Topics include the 
sources and use of funds, capital structure, capital budgeting, dividend policy, and financial 
control. </p>
<p><b>MGT 312 Individual and Organizational Behavior</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3 </p>
<p>Study of internal structure and function of organizations and management practices. Provides 
theoretical and a conceptual base for analyzing relationships among individual, group, and total 
system behavior in achievement of organizational objectives within larger organizational 
environments. </p>
<p><b>MGT 329 Operations/Production Management</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 202 or 241, MGT 216, and MATH 120 </p>
<p>Basic concepts, philosophy, and techniques of analysis for decision-making; analysis of 
structure and dynamic behavior of operating systems; use of computers and quantitative 
models in planning and control. </p>
<p><b>MGT 460 Problems in Policy and Management</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: Senior Standing and CIS 381, FIN 310, FIN 315, MGT 312, MGT 329, 
and MKTG 325 </p>
<p>A capstone course, which integrates the functional areas of business designed to provide 
insight into how business decisions are made. </p>
<p><b>MKTG 325 Basic Marketing Management</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ECON 202 </p>
<p>Introduction to the marketing function in business and other organizations. Environmental 
aspects of market selection and strategy. Analysis of product, pricing, promotion, and 
distribution. </p>
<p><a name="ACCOUNTINGMAJORREQUIREMENTS"><b>ACCOUNTING MAJOR REQUIREMENTS</b> </a></p>
<p><b>ACCT 323 Intermediate Accounting I</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT201 </p>
<p>Fundamental accounting principles of valuation and income determination. Financial accounting 
reporting in concept as well as in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 324 Intermediate Accounting II</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 323 </p>
<p>Continuation of ACCT 323. Accounting principles of valuation and income determination. 
Financial accounting reporting in concept as well as in accordance with generally accepted 
accounting principles </p>
<p><b>ACCT 331 Principles of Taxation</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 202 or 241 </p>
<p>Study of federal income taxation and its application to individual taxpayers and business 
enterprises. Practical problems in making and filing returns. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 342 Advanced Managerial Cost Accounting</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: MGT 217, MGT 312, MGT 329, and ACCT 241 </p>
<p>Concepts, analysis, procedures, and systems optimizing the utility of financial and non financial 
accounting data for managerial decisions. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 350 Junior Accounting Seminar</b> </p>
<p>Credits 1: Prereq: ACCT 323 </p>
<p>Seminar requiring students to research and present specialized accounting topics. (It is 
recommended that this seminar be taken concurrently with ACCT 324.) </p>
<p><b>ACCT 456 Auditing</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 324, ACCT 350 and CIS 382 </p>
<p>Concepts and practices of independent and internal auditing. Professional responsibilities, risk 
assessments, audit planning and reporting. </p>
<p><b>CIS 382 Systems Analysis</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: CIS 381or CIS 220 </p>
<p>Study of basic systems analysis skill, using HIPA charts, structured design, top-down 
approach for the study, design and development phases of the system life cycle. </p>
<p><a name="ACCOUNTINGMAJORELECTIVES"><b>ACCOUNTING MAJOR ELECTIVES</b> </a></p>
<p><b>ACCT 431 Advanced Tax Concepts</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 331 </p>
<p>Specialized federal tax concepts for individuals, business, estates, and trusts. Elaborates on 
basic principles discussed in Principles of Taxation. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 460 Governmental and Not-for-Profit Accounting</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 324 </p>
<p>Accounting and reporting principles, standards and procedures applicable to governmental 
units and not-for-profit institutions, i.e. universities, hospitals. Special consideration to financial 
management problems peculiar to the not-for-profit sector. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 461 Advanced Accounting</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 324 </p>
<p>Study of accounting problems arising in connection with partnerships, corporate affiliation; 
institutional, social, and fiduciary accounting; consignment; installments sales; and foreign 
exchange. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 470 Contemporary Issues in Managerial Accounting</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT 342 </p>
<p>Contemporary topics and emerging issues in managerial accounting. This field is rapidly 
evolving to meet the needs of enterprises competing in a dynamic global environment. </p>
<p><b>ACCT 480 Comparative International Accounting</b> </p>
<p>Credits 3: Prereq: ACCT202 or ACCT 241 </p>
<p>Study of systems that have proven to be problems in an international accounting context, 
particularly for corporate financial reporting. Also, the progress toward international 
harmonization of financial reporting and taxation. </p>
<p><b>CIS AND FINANCE ELECTIVES</b> </p>
<p>Must be approved by the Chair of the Accounting department from senior level (400) CIS 
and Finance major. </p>
<p><b>NOTE:</b> </p>
<p>Beginning in the 1997-1998 academic year, the requirements for an accounting degree will 
change. Where CIS 381 is now required, it will no longer be required. However, students will 
be required to take CIS 220 and CIS 480. Students who start at ISU after spring 1997 will 
be required to comply with these new requirements. Students who have already begun the 
program are encouraged to take these courses, but may graduate under the catalog in effect 
when they started the program. </p>
<p><a name="PROBATIONANDDISMISAL1"><b>PROBATION AND DISMISAL</b> </a></p>
<p>At the end of any semester or summer session, undergraduate students will be placed on 
probation if their cumulative ISU grade point average is below 1.75 for 25 credits or less or 
2.0 for over 25 credits. </p>
<p>Students on scholastic probation who attain a GPA of 2.0 or higher during the next or 
subsequent semester after being placed on probation, but whose cumulative GPA is still below 
the minimum required for their rank, remain on scholastic probation. </p>
<p>Students on scholastic probation who attain a cumulative GPA higher than the minimum 
required on the scholastic probation scale are automatically removed from probation. </p>
<p>A student on probation will be dismissed at the end of any probationary semester or summer 
session in which the student obtains a GPA of less than 2.0 unless the grades earned in that 
semester or summer session are sufficient to take the student off probation. </p>
<p><a name="PETITION1"><b>PETITION</b></a> </p>
<p>A student may petition to the dean or the appropriate committee for consideration of problems 
of curricula or admission which are not covered by stated procedures. Curricular petitions 
must: 1) include a recommendation from the student's advisor, 2) a recommendation by the 
chair of the department offering courses in the subject field or by a special committee 
overseeing the requirements, and 3) catalog copy of descriptions of courses transferred from 
other institution if the course is to be considered in a test of course equivalency. All copies of 
the petition are to be advanced to the Registrar's Office for action after all signatures are 
affixed. Decisions may require several weeks, and notice of the result will be mailed to the 
student. A student may petition: </p>
<ol>
<li>Deletion of Idaho State University grades from computation in the grade point average 
(GPA) under the conditions which follow: <ol>
<li>When a student changes to a radically different curriculum, lower division 
courses which are not required in or appropriate to the new curriculum may be 
eliminated from computation or grade point averages for the purpose of 
determining probation or graduation at the discretion of the dean who has 
responsibility for the new curriculum. </li>
<li>Elimination of computation of courses from grade point average by petition also 
results in the elimination of corresponding course credits. </li>
<li>This adjustment will not be made until the conclusion of one semester in the new 
curriculum. </li>
<li>Courses that satisfy any general education requirements in the university cannot 
be removed from GPA computation, even if alternate courses meeting the 
requirement have been taken. </li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>Academic dismissal and reinstatement. Students will be notified at mid-semester as to 
whether they are doing D or F work in any class. The students' advisors will also 
receive this information so they may work with the students to try to prevent 
probationary status. </li>
<li>Following dismissal, under the scholastic probation ruling, a student on first dismissal 
may be reinstated after a one-semester layout by petitioning the dean. A student on 
second dismissal may be reinstated after a one-year layout by petitioning the college 
dean. No more than two reinstatements will be permitted. A third dismissal is final. 
Students seeking reinstatement prior to expiration of the mandatory layout period may 
petition their dean. The summer session does not qualify for a semester layout. </li>
<li>Substitution of departmental requirements. A student may petition to substitute courses 
in lieu of departmental requirements. The course or courses the student wishes to 
substitutes must be approved by the department chairperson. </li>
<li>Substitution of the general education requirements. A student who transfers from 
another institution may petition to have courses with similar content but different titles 
than those offered at ISU substituted for courses listed in the general education 
requirements. Petitions must be approved by the department chairperson of the 
discipline in which the course being transferred is offered. </li>
<li>General education requirements deficiencies. A transfer student may petition to waive a 
maximum of one credit hour in the area of humanities, social science, or natural science 
to fulfill the general education requirements. This normally pertains to students 
transferring to Idaho State from an institution which uses the quarter system rather that 
the semester system. </li>
<li>Pass-no-Pass option. A student may petition to have a P or NP converted to a letter 
grade. The petition must contain the grade assigned in the class and must be signed by 
the class instructor. </li>
</ol>
<p><a name="GRADUATION1"><b>GRADUATION</b> </a></p>
<p>A cumulative grade point average of 2.0 or higher is required for graduation. In addition, a 
grade point average of at least 2.0 with no grade lower than a &#147;C&#148; in any course required in 
the accounting major. </p>
<p><b>Application for Graduation</b> </p>
<p>To obtain applications for graduation and to pay the $20 graduation/diploma fee, contact the 
Office of Registration and Records. The application should be completed by the student and 
left with the graduation clerk in the Registrar's Office. Please check with the Registrar's Office 
for application deadlines at least one semester prior to your final semester. </p>
<p><b>Minimum Requirements for Graduation</b> </p>
<p>To graduate with a BBA a student must have satisfactorily completed 128 credits of the 
prescribed coursework. In addition: </p>
<ol>
<li>The student must complete at least 64 credits of non-business credits. </li>
<li>Have a minimum of at least a &#147;C&#148; in all accounting courses. </li>
<li>Complete all the required courses in the College of Business with at least a 2.0 GPA. </li>
</ol>
<p><a name="ACADEMICHONORS"><b>ACADEMIC HONORS AT ISU</b> </a></p>
<p><a name="DeansList"><b>Dean's List</b> </a></p>
<p>Full-time undergraduate students who earn at least a 3.5 GPA in any semester will be chosen 
for the Dean's List in that semester. The Registrar's Office calculates GPAs and determines 
which students have qualified for the Dean's List. </p>
<p><a name="Honors"><b>Honors and High Honors Designation </b></a></p>
<p>Students who secure a minimum grade point average of 3.33 and also are in the top 10% of 
their respective college's graduating class are designated as graduating with honors. Those in 
the top 5% of their graduating class graduate with high honors. Honors designations are then 
approved by the student's major department and dean. </p>
<p><a name="BetaGammaSigma"><b>Beta Gamma Sigma</b> </a></p>
<p>Beta Gamma Sigma is a national business honor society. To be eligible for admission into the 
society, students must be in the top 5% of their junior class or the top 10% of their graduating 
class. Initiates are honored each year at the College of Business Awards Banquet. </p>
<p><a name="BetaAlphaPsi"><b>Beta Alpha Psi</b> </a></p>
<p>Beta Alpha Psi is a national honorary accounting fraternity. Members are required to meet 
certain requirements. Requirements include high ethical standards and a minimum grade point 
average. Scholastic requirements for Beta Alpha Psi include: </p>
<ol>
<li>Completion of at least one upper-division accounting course at ISU with a minimum 
average GPA of 3.0 on all accounting courses taken. </li>
<li>Have a 3.0 cumulative GPA for all work completed in all courses. </li>
</ol>
<p><a name="MBA"><b>MASTER OF BUSINESS ADMINISTRATION WITH EMPHASIS IN ACCOUNTING </b></a><b></b></p>
<p>Following a national trend, Idaho law requires that a candidate sitting for the CPA examination 
after the year 1999 must have a college degree with 150 credit hours. While many accounting 
positions can be filled by individuals with a bachelor degree without a CPA certificate, 
graduates intending to progress in a professional career in either managerial or public 
accounting will benefit greatly from the additional breadth and depth offered by a graduate 
degree. </p>
<p>The program strives to produce graduates with the knowledge and skills necessary for 
successful professional accounting careers. Both the undergraduate and graduate degrees 
emphasize characteristics that promote success among graduates, including: </p>
<ul>
<li>business and accounting knowledge, </li>
<li>capability and motivation for continued learning, </li>
<li>competence in learning skills (including research of data bases), </li>
<li>abilities to analyze, critique, and communicate, </li>
<li>abilities to work effectively with others, </li>
<li>interpersonal and leadership skills, and </li>
<li>rigorous ethical standards. </li>
</ul>
<p>The undergraduate degree program prepares accounts with broad knowledge in business and 
accounting suitable for entry level positions in the several career paths available to 
accountants. The MBA Accounting Emphasis program enhances the knowledge and skills for 
rapid advancement in either managerial or public accounting. Students planning to pass the 
Certified Public Accountant (CPA) and Certified Management Accountant (CMA) 
examinations should continue beyond the BBA degree into the MBA. </p>
<p>Students who have gone through the graduate program at Idaho State University consistently 
pass the CPA exam. In 1993, Idaho State University was first in the nation, shattering the 
CPA pass record with a 70% pass rate. This phenomenon exemplifies the quality program 
offered at ISU. Why is ISU's rate consistently in the top 10 in the nation in passing the CPA 
exam? The reason is the quality of professors who foster a learning environment and the 
dedication of students who are willing to work very hard. </p>
<p>The program is designed to last one complete year (30 credits). The four courses constituting 
the accounting emphasis are offered in the spring of each year. Students taking these courses 
will also have to complete the six MBA II courses to earn an MBA. The required courses, 
although anchored in traditional functional fields are designed to provide a strong integrative 
focus building upon the competencies developed during a student's undergraduate years or 
developed in the first year of Graduate School (MBA I). In order to complete the program in 
one year, students will have to plan on taking at least two courses (6 credits) during one 
summer. </p>
<p><a name="ADMISSIONREQUIREMENTS2"><b>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS</b> </a></p>
<p>To enroll in the Graduate Program at Idaho State University, all students must complete their 
undergraduate studies and take the GMAT (Graduate Management Admission Test). The 
MBA program admits only those students that have met the minimum requirements of the 
program outlined in the Graduate Catalog. Applications must be completed and sent in by 
May 1st for summer admission, July 1st for fall semester admission, and December 1st for 
spring admission. </p>
<p>The GMAT is a standardized test administered four times a year at various locations across 
the country. The test consists of quantitative, writing, and analytical components. Students 
registering for the GMAT can pick up registration pamphlets at the MBA office located on the 
5th of the College of Business, the Office of Graduate Studies and Research located on the 
2nd floor of Fine Arts Building, or the Testing Center located on the 3rd floor in Gravely Hall. 
GMAT testing is offered at ISU twice a year-- in June and October. For exact dates, 
locations, and other information pertaining to the GMAT, please refer to the registration 
pamphlet and/or consult your advisor. </p>
<p>There are numerous companies offering home-study materials, software, or classes to help 
you prepare for the GMAT. For example, PrepMaster (1-800-325-5728), Kaplan 
(1-800-KAP-TEST), and The Princeton Review (1-800-955-3700) offer home-study 
materials, software, and classes. Idaho State University (College of Business), Utah State 
University (College of Business), and University of Utah (Adult Continuing Education) all offer 
classes with accompanying home-study materials. Barron's and GMAC offer study guides. 
Barron's study guide can often be purchased in book stores while GMAC's study guide must 
be ordered through the GMAT test registration booklet. These are only a small sample of the 
numerous study and preparation aids available. Students are strongly encouraged to study for 
the GMAT. </p>
<p><a name="GRADUATECOURSEDESCRIPTIONS"><b>GRADUATE COURSE DESCRIPTIONS</b></a> </p>
<table border=1>
<tr><td valign=top>MBA 621: The Decision Making 
Environment <p>(only offered in the Fall Semester)</p>
