Accounting (offered in the Spring 
Semester)</td><td valign=top>Study of legal issues facing accountants, including business 
law, forms of organizations, and regulatory requirements. 
PREREQ: ACCT 456.</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>ACCT 634: Seminar in 
Accounting (offered in the Spring 
Semester)</td><td valign=top>Capstone course integrating special problems of financial, 
managerial, and tax accounting . Emphasis on analytical 
and communication skills. PREREQ: ACCT 332 and 
ACCT 461.</td></tr>
</table>
<p>For a list of other courses and for more complete detail on the MBA program, please see the 
Idaho State University Graduate Catalog. Students obtain this catalog either at the MBA 
office located on the 5th floor of the College of Business or at the Office of Graduate Studies 
and Research located on the 2nd floor of Fine Arts Building. </p>
<p><a name="PROBATIONANDDISMISSAL2"><b>PROBATION AND DISMISSAL</b> </a></p>
<p>Students who fail to maintain a 3.0 GPA in MBA coursework are deemed to be doing 
unsatisfactory work and are subject to review by the College of Business MBA Committee 
and to dismissal from the program. Students who are dismissed for academic reasons can 
apply for re-admission no earlier than four months after dismissal. The College of Business 
discourages applications for re-admission, unless that student can demonstrate their ability to 
perform satisfactorily in the MBA program. Courses in which a grade of D or F has been 
earned will not be counted toward fulfillment of MBA I or MBA II program requirements 
(See the Idaho State University Graduate Catalog for more details). </p>
<p><a name="PETITION2"><b>PETITION</b> </a></p>
<p>A student may petition the Dean of Graduate Studies and Research for exceptions to the rules 
and procedures stated in the Graduate Catalog or for consideration of problems not covered 
by the stated procedures. Petition forms for graduate students are available only from the 
Office of Graduate Studies and Research; undergraduate petitions forms will not be accepted. </p>
<p>A student would use the petition form to petition for: </p>
<ol>
<li>withdrawal from courses after the deadline for withdrawal as stated in the University 
Calendar. </li>
</ol>
<p>2. use of credits more than eight years old to count towards a master's degree. </p>
<p>3. transfer of credits from unclassified to classified status. </p>
<ol>
<li>transfer of more than 30% of credits required for a degree from unclassified to 
classified status. </li>
<li>transfer of more than nine credits from another institution to a master's degree program 
at Idaho State University. </li>
<li>an extension of the maximum time (eight years) allowed for completion of a master's 
degree or educational specialist certificate. </li>
<li>an extension of the maximum time (five years) allowed for completion of a doctoral 
degree after comprehensive examinations have been passed. </li>
</ol>
<p>8. correction of errors or inaccuracies on the student's official transcript. </p>
<p>9. any other deviation from Graduate School policy listed in this catalog. </p>
<p>Petition forms should not be used for: </p>
<ol>
<li>appeals of a grade or of dismissal from a program. See the section on Appeals in the 
Graduate Catalog. </li>
<li>substitutions of courses within degree requirements or waivers of degree requirements. 
Exceptions to degree requirements are requested as a part of the approval process for 
the Program of Study form. </li>
</ol>
<p><a name="GRADUATIONREQUIREMENTS2"><b>GRADUATION REQUIREMENTS</b> </a></p>
<p>Students must apply for graduation a semester before they plan to graduate. This is done by 
going to the registration office located in the Museum Building and filling out an application. 
There is nominal fee for graduation that must be paid before a student graduates. </p>
<p>Along with successfully completing the course requirements, students must pass an oral 
examination in order to graduate. The oral examination consists of an executive summary and 
presentation of a case. The case is given to the student two weeks prior to the presentation. 
The case will be presented to a panel of three professors, two from the College of Business 
and one from outside the College of Business. After the presentation the student who is 
presenting will be asked to leave the room while the three professors evaluate the student's 
performance. After evaluating the student's performance, the professors will notify the student 
whether he/she passed or not. In addition to the presentation, the student must turn in an 
executive summary three working days prior to the case presentation. This summary will also 
be a factor in determining whether or not the student passed. </p>
<p><a name="STUDENTSUPPORTSERVICES">S<b>TUDENT SUPPORT SERVICES AND ORGANIZATIONS</b> </a></p>
<p><a name="CAREERDEVELOPMENT"><b>CAREER DEVELOPMENT AND JOB PLACEMENT</b></a> </p>
<p><a name="Advising"><b>Advising</b> </a></p>
<p>Career advising is available through a variety of sources. Your academic advisor is a valuable 
source of information about careers in accounting. The Counseling and Testing Center on the 
third floor of Gravely Hall can also help you determine a career path if you are undecided. </p>
<p>Students pursuing an undergraduate degree program are assigned academic advisors to assist 
them with educational planning. Those fully accepted for admission who have indicated an 
intent to major in a specific program of study will be assigned an advisor by an academic 
advising coordinator in their respective college or department. </p>
<p>Students who are undecided about their program of study and others who have been identified 
as needing academic assistance are provided academic advising through the Supplemental 
Advising Center. Non-degree seeking students are not assigned advisors unless requested. </p>
<p>Students should always consult their advisor prior to registration to develop an appropriate 
plan of study. To receive this type of help, it is necessary to call your advisor well in advance 
to schedule an appointment. </p>
<p>Since deciding on a career and a course of study is so important, students are encouraged to 
strike out on their own and inquire of individuals who are already in the profession and to look 
for information about the accounting profession in other areas as well (i.e. the internet and 
fellow students). </p>
<p><a name="CareerPlanningandPlacement2"><b>Career Planning and Placement</b> </a></p>
<p>The Career Planning and Placement Center provides career guidance to students and alumni in 
both individual and group settings. This centralized student service program seeks to enhance 
the student's educational experience by promoting the development and implementation of 
career plans. </p>
<p>In assisting students with preparation for potential employment, the Career Planning and 
Placement Center provides the opportunity to open and maintain a credential file; helps 
construct an effective resume, and cover and follow-up letters; assists with preparation for the 
professional interview experience; and offers a wide range of weekly career-related 
workshops. The Center maintains a comprehensive Career Resource/Video library, fosters 
employer contacts, and keeps students informed of current job opportunities through a weekly 
vacancy bulletin and individual announcements.  The Center coordinates on-campus interviews, 
develops off-campus interview opportunities, provides a resume referral system, and 
promotes and maintains a positive working relationship between students and prospective 
employers. The Staff seeks to meet recruiter needs by helping students acquire knowledge of 
what various careers require and after, gain insight into employer expectations, and develop 
realistic views of the world of work in today's employment arena. </p>
<p>Students enrolled in their senior academic year (within one year of expected graduation) may 
register with the Center to gain several additional benefits. These include: entitling them to 
participate in on-campus interviews; receiving the weekly vacancy bulletin; having their 
resumes referred to employers for specific positions; receiving individualized notices of 
off-campus employment opportunities; and having five free sets of credentials mailed. 
Commencing with the sixth set of credentials requested, a fee of $2 is charged for each 
subsequent mailing. </p>
<p>Alumni wishing to reactivate their credential files will be charged a fee of $30. This fee will 
entitle them to receive the weekly vacancy bulletin and individualized notices of employment 
openings in their fields, participate in on-campus interviews, and request the mailing of five free 
sets of their credentials for a period of five free sets of their credentials for a period of one 
academic year. If the reactivating alumnus requests more than five sets of credentials be mailed 
during a given academic year, an additional $2 fee will be charged for each subsequent 
mailing. </p>
<p>An ISU alumnus who will graduate with a post-graduate degree from ISU will not be required 
to pay a fee to reactivate the credential file for a period of one year. However, if a 
post-graduate degree is earned from another institution a reactivation fee of $30 will be 
charged. </p>
<p><a name="Internships"><b>Internships</b> </a></p>
<p>Internships are career-related work experiences incorporating learning goals or an &#147;intentional 
learning agenda.&#148; Internships may be paid or unpaid, for credit or non-credit. Internships are a 
dynamic and worthwhile experience allowing students to test or experience accounting issues 
in a nonacademic environment. Interested students can find out more about available 
internships through the Career Planning and Placement service and through announcements 
made at Beta Alpha Psi meetings. Occasionally announcements of available internships are 
made in some accounting classes. </p>
<p><a name="STUDENTORGANIZATIONS"><b>STUDENT ORGANIZATIONS</b> </a></p>
<p>With the demands of accounting professionals continuously changing and becoming more 
competitive, it is necessary for students to supplement their technical training with activities that 
will develop equally important leadership and personal skills. The best place to develop the 
additional skills is in ISU's student organizations. Students who actively participate and make 
meaningful contributions to ISU's student organizations will enhance their educational 
experience and gain a competitive advantage in the workforce. ISU currently has two student 
organizations for accounting students &#150; Beta Alpha Psi and the ISU Accounting Association. </p>
<p><b>Beta Alpha Psi</b> </a></p>
<p>Beta Alpha Psi is an honorary fraternity with 115 chapters throughout the nation. The ISU 
chapter is called Eta Lambda. It is governed and run by accounting students at ISU each year. 
There are annual elections held each year to select students to serve as officers in the local 
chapter. Officers perform various functions and oversee the work of committees established 
within the organization. Officers also have the unique opportunity of going to national meetings 
to learn about the functions of Beta Alpha Psi and to receive training and instruction. These 
national meetings provide a unique opportunity for the officers as they are held in America's 
major cities and involves student chapters from all over the country. </p>
<p>All students have opportunities to develop leadership skills. Those students who do not serve 
as officers within the chapter have a number of opportunities to serve as a chairperson of one 
of the various committees. These positions provide invaluable experience as students plan, 
prepare, and delegate; interact with both students, professionals, and professors; and work to 
reach goals and complete tasks. </p>
<p>Students who do not serve as officers of as a chairperson of one the committees still have 
opportunities to serve and develop professional skills. Through serving on one of the various 
committees, students can interact with other accounting students and learn more about the 
organization and functions. In so doing, students will be prepared to chair committees in future 
years. Students will also have a chance to come in contact with professors and professionals 
through fulfilling and carrying out assignments within the committees. This exposure will 
provide students with insights into the profession and help them develop relationships and 
contacts that will prove invaluable in future employment endeavors. </p>
<p>Because Beta Alpha Psi is an honor society, members are required to meet certain 
requirements. Requirements include high ethical standards and a minimum grade point average. 
Scholastic requirements for Beta Alpha Psi include: </p>
<ol>
<li>Completion of at least one upper-division accounting courses at ISU with a minimum 
average GPA of 3.0 on all accounting courses taken. </li>
<li>Have a 3.0 cumulative GPA for all work completed in all courses. </li>
</ol>
<p>An active professional program is conducted by Beta Alpha Psi each year including guest 
speakers from the accounting profession, panel discussions, field trips, and other activities 
designed to promote professional awareness. Members of Beta Alpha Psi provide services to 
the School through the tutoring program. Services to the external community are provided in 
the form of VITA (voluntary income tax assistant) program and the Adopt-a-Highway 
program. </p>
<p>Students can join Beta Alpha Psi if they meet the requirements above and attend and actively 
participate in Beta Alpha Psi. There is a one-time fee paid to National Beta Alpha Psi to join 
and annual local dues for members. New members are honored each semester at an initiation 
banquet. </p>
<p><a name="ISUACCOUNTINGSOCIETY"><b>ISU ACCOUNTING SOCIETY</b> </a></p>
<p>The ISU Accounting Society participates in activities with Beta Alpha Psi. The requirements 
for membership are not as stringent as those for membership in Beta Alpha Psi, but students 
still have the opportunity to serve on Beta Alpha Psi committees and participate in Beta Alpha 
Psi activities. Such participation provides unique and valuable opportunities. </p>
<p>Active participation in Accounting Club/Beta Alpha Psi is very important for developing your 
professional skills. Accounting majors should join and become involved as soon as possible. 
The club provides many benefits to its members, including but not limited to: </p>
<ul>
<li>exposure to professional speakers </li>
<li>enhancement of leadership skills </li>
<li>exercise of entrepreneurial skills </li>
<li>getting to know the faculty and other students </li>
<li>reduced costs for members in the Beta Alpha Psi CPA Review Program. </li>
</ul>
<p><a name="CPAREVIEWANDPREPCOURSE"><b>ISU/BETA ALPHA PSI CPA REVIEW AND PREP COURSE</b> </a></p>
<p>For many years, ISU has been able to boast a nationally recognized pass rate on the Uniform 
CPA exam. One of the reasons is that Beta Alpha Psi offers a unique review and prep course. 
The course is taught by expert accounting professionals teaching at ISU and utilizes materials 
developed by ISU professors and used in a nationally prominent review course produced by 
Accounting Institute Seminars, Inc. (AIS). </p>
<p>Students and professionals enrolled in the course have the unique opportunity to gain in-depth 
knowledge of the exam and to receiving instruction from some of the best instructors in the 
nation in their respective fields. In the past, students who have successfully passed the CPA 
exam contribute success to the principles taught in the course. Specifically, students attribute 
the scheduling, prioritizing, and analytical skills developed in the course to their success. 
Students have also found greater success when taking the course concomitantly with the 
Graduate level accounting courses. Together, the course and graduate courses, provide an 
intense program which develops the mind and prepares students for the CPA exam and 
beyond. </p>
<p>Students who are serious about pursuing a career in professional accounting should contact a 
member of Beta Alpha Psi who are planning and organizing the course for the spring in which 
you intend to take the exam. </p>
<p><a name="STUDENTADVISORYBOARD"><b>STUDENT ADVISORY BOARD</b></a> </p>
<p>The Student Advocacy Panel serves as a liaison between accounting students and the 
accounting program faculty. Beta Alpha Psi/Accounting Society selects two sophomores, two 
juniors, two seniors, and two graduate students to serve as panel members. The members 
attend luncheon meetings with the accounting faculty and voice students' complaints, questions, 
needs, or other concerns. If you would like to be considered for selection as a panel member 
you should contact Beta Alpha Psi/Accounting Society in BA 111. </p>
<p><a name="OTHERPERTINENTINFORMATION"><b>OTHER PERTINENT INFORMATION</b> </a></p>
<p><a name="FINDINGASSISTANCE"><b>FINDING ASSISTANCE</b> </a></p>
<p>There are numerous sources at ISU designed to assist students. Students can find academic 
assistance with the help of tutors, study labs, the Academic Skills Center, or TRIO Student 
Services. ISU also offers computer labs and workshops for students. For financial assistance, 
students can apply for help through the Financial Aid Office, the Scholarship Office, or apply 
for scholarships through the College of Business. </p>
<p><a name="ACADEMICASSISTANCE"><b>ACADEMIC ASSISTANCE</b> </a></p>
<p>The Accounting Lab offers free assistance to students in accounting courses. The Lab is 
located in BA 111 and hours are determined each semester (hours will be posted on the 
door). The Business Statistics Lab offers free assistance to students in statistics courses. The 
Business Statistics Lab is located in BA 111 and hours are determined each semester. </p>
<p>The Academic Skills Center is located on the top floor of the Museum Building (Room 434, 
phone 236-3662). The Center helps students with reading and study skills, mathematics, 
English (for speakers of other languages), and writing assignments. Certified tutors and 
professional staff provide one-on-one and small-group instruction without charge to all full- or 
part-time students. Hours are established each semester and tutoring hours are also scheduled 
in Idaho Falls. </p>
<p>For those who qualify, TRIO Student Services is also a source of assistance. TRIO Student 
Services is a multifaceted, federally-funded student assistance program for those students who 
are low-income, first generation college students, or disabled and need transportation and/or 
special accessibility orientation. TRIO Student Services is located in the Museum Building 
across from the Registration Office; they may also be reached by calling 236-3242. </p>
<p><a name="COMPUTERFACILITIES"><b>COMPUTER FACILITIES AND SERVICES</b> </a></p>
<p>The Computer Service Center, located in the basement of the College of Business building, is 
dedicated to meeting the computing needs of students. Frequent computer workshops are 
offered to students free of charge. Monthly workshop schedules are available at the Computer 
Center Administrative Office (Room B-24) and in most microcomputer labs. </p>
<p>Microcomputer labs are available to all students at nine locations on campus and in Idaho 
Falls. Labs are staffed seven days a week and each lab maintains separate hours. A 
combination of DOS based microcomputers are located in each Microcomputer LANs with 
Apple Macintosh computers and X-Terminals available in specific lab locations. A wealth of 
software and services are available as well as access to the student information database and 
the Internet. All services can also be accessed remotely. </p>
<p>To use the microcomputer labs, you must have a Novell LAN account. The cost of a LAN 
account is $10.00 per semester and $5.00 for summer session. </p>
<p>Lab locations are: </p>
<ul>
<li>College of Business basement </li>
<li>Turner Hall basement </li>
<li>College of Education Instructional Materials Center </li>
<li>College of Pharmacy, Room 232 </li>
<li>Student Union Building, fourth floor </li>
<li>Liberal Arts Building, Room 270 </li>
<li>Oboler Library basement </li>
<li>University Place in Idaho Falls </li>
</ul>
<p><a name="PROFESSIONALEXAMINATIONS"><b>PROFESSIONAL EXAMINATIONS</b> </a></p>
<p>The Certified Public Accountant (CPA) examination is a 2-day exam offered twice a year in 
May and November. The exam covers business law and professional responsibilities, auditing, 
taxation, managerial accounting and reporting, accounting in governmental and not-for-profit 
organizations, and financial accounting and reporting. For more information and registration 
materials, contact the Idaho State Board of Accountancy, 1109 Main St., Suite 470, Owyhee 
Plaza, Boise, ID 83720 or phone (208) 334-2490. Idaho State University offers an excellent 
CPA Review Program. </p>
<p>The Certified Internal Auditor (CIA) examination is administered by The Institute of Internal 
Auditors every May and November. This is a 2-day examination and covers internal audit 
process, internal audit skills, management control and information technology, and the audit 
environment. The popularity of this exam has been growing over the last few years. Students 
can take the exam for half price while enrolled in school. For more information and for 
application materials, contact IIA Customer Service at (407) 830-7600. </p>
<p>The Certified Management Accountant (CMA) examination is administered by the Institute of 
Certified Management Accountants every June and December. The test is in four parts and 
covers Economics, Finance, and Management; Financial Accounting and Reporting; 
Management Reporting, Analysis, and Behavioral Issues; and Decision Analysis and 
Information Systems. For application materials, study guides, or more information, contact the 
ICMA Office at 1-800-638-4427. </p>
<p><a name="FINANCIALASSISTANCE"><b>FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE</b> </a></p>
<p>Numerous forms of financial aid are available which include employment, grants, loans, tuition 
waivers, scholarships, service awards, and benefits for veterans and their dependents. The 
Financial Aid Office, a good starting point, is located on the third floor of the Museum Building 
(Room 337, phone 236-2756). Next door to the Financial Aid Office is the Scholarship 
Office, located on the third floor of the Museum Building (Room 327, phone 236-3315). The 
Idaho State University Undergraduate Catalog lists all resources to contact for information on 
financial aid and scholarships. </p>
<p>Scholarships are also available through the Undergraduate Studies Office in the College of 
Business, room 510. Scholarships are primarily based on academic performance at ISU but 
consideration is also given to those students with financial need. Applications are usually due 
March 1st for the following fall semester and November 15th for the following spring 
semester. </p>
<p>Students preparing to enter the MBA program at ISU can apply for graduate assistantships 
through the MBA office (BA 510). Appointments are for the nine-month academic year and 
require twenty hours of work per week. Students may be assigned to assist faculty, teach labs, 
develop software, or other duties needed by the department. Graduate assistantships offer a 
tuition waiver and a stipend of approximately $6000. Award decisions are based upon 
GMAT scores, undergraduate GPA, and the match between the department's needs and the 
skills and experience of the individual. Students must first be admitted to the MBA program to 
be considered for an assistantship. Applications are generally due two months before the first 
semester of study, however, interested students should confirm deadlines well in advance. </p>
<p><a name="SCHOLARSHIPSAVAILABLE"><b>SCHOLARSHIPS AVAILABLE</b> </a></p>
<p>There are numerous scholarships available to accounting students through the College of 
Business and ASISU. They include: </p>
<ul>
<li>Cooper Norman </li>
<li>Deloitte &amp; Touche </li>
<li>Crawford Moore </li>
<li>ASISU Scholarships </li>
<li>Farmers Insurance </li>
<li>Lockheed </li>
<li>Tax Institute </li>
<li>American Governmental Accounting </li>
</ul>
<p>This is not an all inclusive list and some of these scholarships have specific requirements that 
must be met to qualify for the award. There is also one scholarship available only to Graduate 
students in accounting: The M.T. and Jennie Deaton Scholarship. </p>
<hr>
<h4>Footnotes</h4>
<p><a name="FOOTNOTE_1">[1]</a> A. Arens &amp; J. Loebbecke. <i>Auditing: An Integrated Approach. 5th Edition.</i> Prentice 
Hall, New Jersey, 1991. </p>
<p><a name="FOOTNOTE_2">[2]</a> M. C. Francis, T.C. Mulder, and J. S. Stark. <i>Intentional Learning: A Process for 
Learning to Learn in the Accounting Curriculum. </i>Sarasota: Accounting Education Change 
Commission and American Accounting Association, 1995, p.6. </p>
<p><a name="FOOTNOTE_3">[3]</a> Ibid. p. 93. </p>
</body>

