<P>
Microsoft will provide temporary licenses after grant applications have been approved, for use while materials requested are being prepared.  You must be willing to provide the materials requested for the level of grant awarded in complete and good order prior to the expiration of the temporary license.  If materials are provided by the due date, permanent licenses will be issued as long as your school remains in compliance with the terms of the grant.
<P>

</font>
<font size=3><a name="02">
<B>Faculty Qualifications </b></a><P></font>
<font size=2>

Full-time faculty in any department responsible for any of the following may apply:
<ul>

<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> Teaching programming or the use of programming for problem-solving activities, software engineering, or other information technology curricula involving programming tools. 
These departments include but are not limited to Computer Science, Business Information Technologies, Engineering, or Math. <br>

<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> Teaching project management. <br>


<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> Creatively using desktop software to provide solutions, projects, modeling, or curricula specific to a discipline. Examples include using Microsoft Excel to teach statistics or using Microsoft Office to study work flow. 
</ul>

Note: The Instructional Grant Program will accept only one application per department within each college or university. We will accept multiple applications per school. 
<P>
</font>
<font size=3><a name="03">
<B>Facility Requirements</B></a> </font>
<font size=2>
<P>

<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> Your school must have a Web site where course syllabi and other materials are posted.<br> 

<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> You must have access to e-mail on the Internet.<br> 

<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> You must have at least 25 computers in lab facilities within your department, each having a 486 processor or better and a minimum of 8 megabytes (MB) of RAM. These computers must meet the system requirements specified for the products you are requesting.<br>
 
<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> Applications will not be accepted from any department within a college or university that was awarded an instructional lab grant in any previous year but that did not fulfill its commitment to either the spirit or the stated requirements of that program.<br>

<IMG SRC="gifs/bullet.gif" ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="5" HEIGHT="8" BORDER="0"> Your computer lab must be able to run Windows 95&reg; or Windows NT&reg;.

<P></font>
<font size=3><a name="04">
<B>Upgrading Software</b></a></font>
<font size=2>
<P>

The Instructional Grant Program permits you to upgrade your software with new versions during the award period by acquiring one copy of the upgraded product and copying the upgraded software to all computers affected by the awarded licenses.  Rules for maintenance are different for the first and second years. 
<P>
<B>First Year Maintenance Upgrades</B> 
<P>
The software license agreement provided to grant recipients allows schools to update their labs with the latest version of application, language, database, and system software for which they receive a license under the grant program for a one-year period from the date of award. To upgrade the computers with software licensed through the grant program, the recipient needs to purchase from a reseller one copy of each product licensed under the grant program. 
<P>
<B>Second Year Maintenance Upgrades </B>
<P>
During the spring of 1998, all posted syllabi and course materials will be checked against the original applications. Those schools having met their commitments will receive an additional license that permits them to upgrade the software to the next version, as described in the paragraph above. 
<P>
<B>Upgrades Beyond the Second Year</B> 
<P>
There will be no further maintenance upgrades beyond the second year under this program. All licenses will continue to be current under grant for installed software. You will be able to continue using the software as is. 

<P>
</font>
<font size=3><a name="05">
<b>Time Line </b></a></font>
<font size=2>
<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=5>
<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Open application process</td>
<td valign=top align=left><font size=2>Sept 1 - Dec 1, 1996</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Application evaluation</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<font size=2>Dec 2 - Feb 15, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Award acceptance letters and temporary licenses sent  - call for materials and URLs</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<font size=2>Feb 17, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Electronic reminder sent to all grant recipients of requirements to be in compliance with temporary and permanent licenses</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<font size=2>May 1, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Acknowledgement of temporary licenses must be signed and returned to Microsoft.</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<font size=2>May 15, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Award recipients submit disks with course syllabi and course materials and archival copy.</td>
<td valign=top align=left>  
<font size=2>Mar 17 - May 15, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Temporary Licenses expire</td>
<td valign=top align=left>  
<font size=2>Jul 1, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Links set up from Curriculum Project to curriculum materials</td>
<td valign=top align=left>  
<font size=2>May 15 - Aug 15, 1997</td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left width=250>
<font size=2>Web sites will be audited by Microsoft for compliance with requirements</td>
<td valign=top align=left>  
<font size=2>Jul 1, 1997</td></tr>
</table>
<P>



Microsoft reserves the right to revoke licenses if signed licenses are not returned in the given time frame, if course syllabi and materials for a designated semester are not submitted, or if submitted materials do not meet the minimum requirement of usability by other faculty. 

<P>

</font>
<font size=3><a name="06">
<b>How to Apply</b></a> </font>
<font size=2>
<P>


You must download and complete the online grant application, which was created using Microsoft Visual Basic. For directions on how to use the grant application, see the Grant Application Help file. 
<P>
To download the application and associated help files, go to <a href="ftp://msdeved.isu.edu/pub/ms/grant97.exe"> ftp://msdeved.isu.edu/pub/ms/grant97.exe</a>   

<P>
<b>Submitting the Application </b><P>

1. Click the Print button at the end of the Grant application or the Print command on the File menu to print a copy of your application.
<P> 
2. Click either the Save Grant Request button at the end of the Grant application or the Save Grant command on the File menu to save your file. Use up to the first eight characters of your e-mail name (excluding the ampersand @) to name the file.
<P>  
3. Save the *.gnt file to a 3.5" disk.
<P> 
4. Write a cover letter on school letterhead. The cover letter should comprise only one sentence that includes the name of the file. Use the Additional Institution Information field in the Grant application to enter any other information you would like to convey and that is ordinarily included in a cover letter.) 
<P> 
5.Send the disk, the cover letter, a sample of either your course syllabus or course materials that will be posted on the Web, and a signed printout of the completed grant application form to: 
<P> 


Microsoft Academic Cooperative<BR>
Microsoft Corporation<BR>
One Microsoft Way<BR>
Redmond, WA 98052-6399 <p>

<b>Important:</b> Applications will not be accepted for review unless you submit the cover letter on college or university letterhead, the signed printout of the completed grant application form, and the sample course syllabus or other course materials you will post to the Web.  We will send you e-mail to confirm receipt of your application. 

<p>

If you have questions about the application process, review the Grant Instructions Help file or the description of the Instructional Grant Program posted at the Microsoft Academic Cooperative  Web site (http://msdeved.isu.edu/ms).   If you need further assistance, please send e-mail to <a href="mailto:GrantQuestion@msdeved.isu.edu">GrantQuestion@msdeved.isu.edu</a>. We will try to answer your questions within 48 hours. 

<p>
We're looking forward to hearing from you. Your participation will help this program succeed in building a mutually supportive electronic community for curriculum sharing and course development. 


<P>
<font size=2>
To discover how previous Instructional Grant recipients have used their grants to create innovative, dynamic courses for their students, <a href="/scripts/participating.idc?">visit the participating institutions.</a>

</font>

<P>
