<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>	CIS 120</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<h2><center>CIS 120</center></h2>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Introduction to Computer Information Systems</B> - Fall Semester
&#145;96</CENTER>
<br>
<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=217>Instructor: James C. Frost</TD><TD WIDTH=150>Office: Rm. 509B
</TD><TD WIDTH=138>Phone: 236-4549</TD><TD WIDTH=216>e-mail: frost@smaug.isu.edu
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=217>Professor: Corey D. Schou</TD><TD WIDTH=150>Office: Rm. 509A
</TD><TD WIDTH=138>Phone: 236-3194</TD><TD WIDTH=216>e-mail: schou@smaug.isu.edu
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=217>Instructor: Mike Anderson</TD><TD WIDTH=150>Office: Idaho Falls 
</TD><TD WIDTH=138>Phone: 535-7802</TD><TD WIDTH=216>e-mail: andemike@if.if.isu.edu
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
<BR>
<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=115>Lecture:</TD><TD WIDTH=192>Rm.  BA 135 in Pocatello
</TD><TD WIDTH=48>Lab:</TD><TD WIDTH=114>Rm. BA 507C</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=115>Lecture &amp; Lab:</TD><TD WIDTH=192>Idaho Falls - CHE 202
</TD><TD WIDTH=48></TD><TD WIDTH=114></TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
 This class is designed to provide the student with the basic computer
competency/literacy to proceed with a college education and career.
 It will involve a basic knowledge of both hardware and software
as well the technology of the computer revolution/ evolution.
 We will work with IBM compatible computers and emphasize the
personal computer.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><I><B>TEXT: </B>Using Information Technology 2<SUP>nd</SUP>
Edition </I> from IRWIN by Williams, Sawyer, &amp; Hutchinson<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
 The attached syllabus identifies the chapter for each week's
lecture, although we may vary depending on class interest and
motivation during the lecture series.  It is to your advantage
to study the reading material prior to each lecture and lab. 
You will retain more from each lecture and lab if you study and
read the material assigned from your text and lab manual.<BR>

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=Right ALT="Figure 1 - ENIAC COMPUTER" SRC="eniac.GIF">
<P>

 We meet for two 50 minute lectures each week and once a week for
lab (two hours - hands-on experience) time.  Additional material
(out-of-book) is discussed during lecture and there will be at
least three pop-quizzes during the semester.  You are tested on
material from lecture, text book, and lab.  Your grade is determined
along the following weighted scale:<BR>

<P>
Lecture exams (3) 40%
<P>
Final exam <I>(<B>Comprehensive</B></I><B>)</B> 25%
<P>
Questions  and pop-quizzes 10%
<P>
Lab work 25%<BR>
<BR>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<B>QUESTION SETS</B>
<P>
 The question sets are stored weekly on the ISU network for your
completion with a word processor for submission the following
week. These weekly question sets are due during class on the established
date and there is a penalty for late turn-ins:
<UL>
<LI>Turn-in after class and up to one day (24 hours) late reduces
the total grade by 10 points;
<LI>If the assignment is turned-in after that, the grade is reduced
by one-half (a 90% becomes 45%).
<LI>Assignments are not accepted after one week (with exception
of documented illness).
</UL>

<P>
Completing the questions will increase your competency of the
Greek-like terms and concepts associated with the silicon idol.
 DO YOUR OWN INDEPENDENT WORK!!  Submitting someone else's questions
will result in a <U>zero</U> for 10% of your CIS 120 grade.  This
will also involve the use of CD-ROM technology.<BR>

<P>
<B>LAB WORK</B>
<P>
The lab meets a each week and attributes 25% of your CIS 120 grade.
 The assignment is available at lab time and due at the end of
each lab period (barring equipment failure).  We often will discuss
the lab assignment during lecture.  Also, a lecture on the topic
of the week is provided at the first of the lab session.    You
must complete your work in lab during the time allotted (2 hours).
There is a final in the lab which constitutes 50% of your lab
grade.<BR>

<P>
<B>EXAMS</B>
<P>
Contact your instructor prior to an exam if you are unable (deathly
ill) to attend an exam, otherwise, no credit is given and a zero
is assigned for that opportunity.  Anyone found cheating (see
student handbook) will receive a minimum of a zero for that exam
(or a 'F' for the class).  The comprehensive finals will require
a picture ID for admission.  <BR>

<P>
Final grades are assigned along the following distributions:<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=126>90 - 100</TD><TD WIDTH=36>A</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=126>80 - 89</TD><TD WIDTH=36>B</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=126>70 -  79</TD><TD WIDTH=36>C</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=126>60 -  69</TD><TD WIDTH=36>D</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=126>Below 60</TD><TD WIDTH=36>F</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
<br>

