Schnieder</FONT>
<H1>Software<BR>
</H1>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>This course will use Microsoft Visual Basic 4.016bit.
 The software is available in those computing center labs that
use Windows95.  You may purchase a version for your home machine,
but you are responsible for turning in assignments in 4.0-16bit.</FONT>
<H1>Grading</H1>

<H2>Assignment Overview</H2>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Quizzes and class participation 5%</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Assignments   50%</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Midterms (2@10% each)  20%</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Final Exam   25%</FONT>
<H2>Student Responsibilities</H2>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Students are responsible for preparing for class
by reading pre-assigned readings and other completing assignments.
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Students may collaborate on design and programming
issues.  This does NOT include duplication of programs or form
designs.  Collaboration should be use to find bugs in programs
or to solve program syntax and general structure problems. Copying
of code, regardless of the number of editor changes, renaming,
and/or retyping is considered cheating, and a student's inability
to describe the function of a handed-in assignment will be considered
defacto evidence of cheating. Cheating will be dealt with in the
strongest possible terms including expulsion from the University
is possible.</FONT>
<H2>Virus Infected Disks</H2>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Assignments handed in on disk will be virus scanned.
 Any assignments turned in on a virus infected disk will be returned
without being graded.  The assignment may be turned in again with
the usual <B>Late Assignment Policy</B> acting from the original
assignment due date.</FONT>
<H2>Late Assignment Policy</H2>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Late assignments will be penalized 10% per day including
weekends from the time the assignment is due.  Assignments turned
less than 24 hours after the due date will be penalized for one
day (10%).  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>NOTE: Late assignments may be mailed to: <B>beard@isu.edu</B>
to avoid missing points for weekends, and such. Any address other
that this is unacceptable.  Any mailed assignment will be graded
based on the delivery time listed on the CIS server system.</FONT>
<H2>Program Requirements</H2>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>All programming assignments must conform to the variable
and object naming standards listed in <B>Appendix II </B>of this
syllabus except when specifically mentioned when the assignment
is assigned.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>In general programs will be graded based on meeting
assignment specifications, use of standard interface design, modular
code, code readability, and internal documentation.  Code readability
includes indenting and formatting code so that it may be easily
read.  A concise block comment should be placed at the top of
each procedure and function including your name, date, and a single
sentence without &quot;ands&quot; or &quot;ors&quot; that exactly
describes what the function or procedure does.  Additional documentation
should be included in critical places through the code to explain
specific situations and decisions.  See <B>Appendix III</B> for
examples of code documentation and code format.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>A well-styled minimal working program is necessary
for a &quot;B&quot; grade on a programming assignment; an &quot;A&quot;
grade will be given for well-styled working solutions that incorporate
additional visual basic controls and features. Only solutions
that are substantially working are acceptable; non-working solutions
will receive a grade of &quot;D&quot; or &quot;F&quot;.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>NOTICE:  As of assignment 3, all modules and forms
MUST have in their &quot;Declaration&quot; section must have the
key word &quot;Option Explicit&quot; defined and each variable
must be defined using a &quot;DIM&quot; statement.</FONT>
