<P></P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Student Responsibilities</P><DIR>
<DIR>

</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Students may collaborate on the design and programming issues.  This does NOT include duplication of entire programs, or form designs.  Collaboration should be use to find bugs in programs or to solve program syntax and general structure problems.  Individual procedures may be duplicated between students; however, these procedures / function may not account for more than 10% of the total line count of the program.  </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Any procedure / function that is to be copied from one student to another or from another source must have the name of the original programmer / source at the top of the procedure - this includes procedures duplicated and then modified to meet slightly different needs.  See <B>Appendix III</B> for examples of code documentation.  Failure to document the source of any code is considered cheating / plagiarism and appropriate measures will be taken.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>NOTE:  Code may be duplicated from <B>Appendix III</B> of this manual with out documenting its source.</P></DIR>
</DIR>

</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Virus Infected Disks</P><DIR>
<DIR>

</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Assignments handed in on disk will be virus scanned.  Any assignments turned in on a virus-infected disk will be returned without being graded.  The assignment may be turned in again with the usual <B>Late Assignment Policy</B> acting from the original assignment due date.</P></DIR>
</DIR>

</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Late Assignment Policy</P><DIR>
<DIR>

</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Late assignments will be penalized 10% per day including weekends from the time the assignment is due.  Assignments turned less than 24 hours after the due date will be penalized for one day (10%).  </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>NOTE: Late assignments may be mailed to: <B>WINGERT@CIS.ISU.EDU</B> to avoid missing points for weekends, and such. Any address other than the one above is unacceptable.  Any mailed assignment will be graded based on the delivery time listed on the CIS server system.</P></DIR>
</DIR>

</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Program Requirements</P><DIR>
<DIR>

</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>All programming assignments must conform to the variable and object naming standards listed in <B>Appendix II </B>of this syllabus except when specifically mentioned when the assignment is assigned.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>In general programs will be graded based on meeting assignment specifications, use of standard interface design, modular code, code readability, and internal documentation.  Code readability includes indenting and formatting code so that it may be easily read.  Internal documentation should be placed at the top of each procedure and function to describe its what the procedure should do.  Additional documentation should be included in critical places through the code to explain specific situations and decisions.  See <B>Appendix III</B> for examples of code documentation and code format.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>NOTICE:  All modules and forms MUST have in their &quot;Declaration&quot; section must have the key word &quot;Option Explicit&quot; defined OR each variable must be defined using a &quot;DIM&quot; statement or a type identifier (%, &amp;, #, !, etc).</P></DIR>
</DIR>

