<body background="grytxtr3.jpg" bgcolor="ffffff">

<h1 align="center"><b>CIS 482/582 </b></h1>

<h2 align="center"><b>Systems Analysis and Design II </b></h2>

<h2 align="center"><b>C.D. Schou Room 509</b> </h2>

<p align="center"><a href="mailto:Schou@SDSC.ISU.EDU"><b>Schou@SDSC.ISU.EDU</b></a><b> </b></p>

<p>The primary objective of this course is to give Accounting,
Computer Information Systems, Computer Science and business
students an opportunity to practice the skills acquired in the
other courses. Elements will be drawn from CIS 382, 381, 220,
221, 480, Acct. 201, 202, 241, FIN 315, MKT 325 and M&amp;O 216,
217, 329. Understanding of basic accounting, finance and marketing
principles is also useful. The course is experiential in nature
i.e., the student will be required to produce results for use by
real individuals and will be evaluated both on process and product.
The course is based on the Intentional learning processes. </p>

<hr>

<h2>Philosophy: </h2>

<blockquote>
    <p><i>&quot;Men are men before they are lawyers, or
    physicians, or merchants, or manufacturers; and if you make
    them capable and sensible men, they will make themselves
    capable and sensible lawyers or physicians. What professional
    men should carry away with them from an University, is not professional
    knowledge, but that which should direct the use of their professional
    knowledge, and bring the light of general culture to
    illuminate the technicalities of a special pursuit. Men may
    be competent lawyers without general education, but it
    depends on general education to make them philosophic
    lawyers--who demand, and are capable of apprehending, principles,
    instead of merely cramming their memory with details. And so
    of all other useful pursuits, mechanical included. Education makes
    a man a more intelligent shoemaker, if that be his
    occupation, but not by teaching him how to make shoes; it
    does so by the mental exercise it gives, and the habits it impresses.&quot;</i>
    -- J. S. Mill, Inaugural Address at St. Andrews </p>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<h2>Schedule: </h2>

<p>The class will meet at 08:00 Monday, Wednesday and Friday.
About 75% of class time will be devoted to group activities. The
remainder will be involved in student faculty interactions. In
order to complete the projects, you will be expected to
participate in group/class activities outside the scheduled
period. Early in the course, I may lecture on basic subjects
needed to get the team moving. In addition, I will prepare
special lectures on issues the group considers important. </p>

<hr>

<h2>Project: </h2>

<p>During the term, a series of projects will be assigned to the
class. The number, frequency and complexity will be determined by
the professor during the term. I will be assuming many roles during
the class. If there is a question about the role, ask me. I may
be a venture capitalist, a customer, a competitor, a facilitator,
etc.. It is the responsibility of the class to establish organizational
structures to carry out these projects using professional
standards. For each project, the class will be responsible for
the following minima: </p>

<ol>
    <li>Business Plan</li>
    <li>Feasibility analysis and proposal </li>
    <li>Cost estimates </li>
    <li>Project schedules </li>
    <li>Hardware and software recommendations (if appropriate) </li>
    <li>Progress reports </li>
    <li>Final reports including <i>inter alia</i> <ol type="a"
        start="1">
            <li>Documentation </li>
            <li>Operating instructions </li>
            <li>Software </li>
            <li>Training materials </li>
            <li>Software repair procedures </li>
            <li>Procedure documents </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
</ol>

<hr>

<h2>Grading: </h2>

<p>You are required to maintain a hardbound contemporaneous
journal of your activities associated with the course </p>

<ol>
    <li>Group Projects Outcome 60% </li>
    <li>Individual Evaluation 30% </li>
    <li>Journal/Log book 5% </li>
    <li>Initiative 5% </li>
</ol>

<p>Since this course is participatory in nature, no provision is
made for missed work. All work is due not later than one week
prior to the scheduled final examination </p>

<p>Think About The Following: </p>

<ol>
    <li>Are there ethical considerations you have missed while
        doing the project? </li>
    <li>How would one calculate the payback on a project? </li>
    <li>Explain how to calculate the break-even point of a
        project. </li>
    <li>Explain the relationship between top down design and
        bottom up testing. </li>
    <li>Could your project be marketed overseas? </li>
    <li>Explain structured walk-through in detail including
        participants and outcomes. </li>
    <li>What is the time relationship between programming,
        documentation, design, and testing? </li>
    <li>What are the components of a system proposal? </li>
    <li>What is work breakdown structure? </li>
    <li>Explain dataflow diagrams and their relationship to
        organization charts, program flowcharts, and system
        flowcharts. </li>
    <li>What is the difference between a requirement and a
        specification? </li>
    <li>What is the relationship between the systems analyst and
        the system tester? </li>
    <li>Could your organization be viable in the 'real world'</li>
</ol>

<hr>

<h2>Final Comments: </h2>

<p>Please remember, this course is not a textbook or case course
(CIS 382). The clients will be real people with real problems.
You are an essential element in a group of professionals who must manage
the projects to solve your clients' problems. I suggest that you
select a leader and get started. You are empowered to fire your
team members. This action should not be taken lightly. It does
not fail the student in the class...It returns the student to the
environment. If you exercise this option, you should follow your
published organizational procedures. If the student protests the firing,
I will convene a review board consisting of two faculty and one
alumnus of the 482 class. The decision of the review board will
be final.</p>

<p>The professor reserves the right to include a final
examination in the course (replacing Project Outcome) if it is
believed that the class has not grasped the important elements of
the course. The final examination in the course will be a
comprehensive essay and case. The student should be able to
integrate the contents of the experiential activity, readings and
lecture. </p>

<hr>

<h2>Text Book: </h2>

<p>In addition to <i>TQM In Software Development</i>, AND The <i>Mythical
Man Month</i> you are expected to purchase any materials you need
to run your company and use the library and other sources for
reference. If it appears that a substantial outlay of funds will
be necessary, notify me.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Software: </h2>

<p>As part of our curriculum development and upgrade process, all
software developed for this course will be for a Windows NT/95
environment. The following Microsoft development packages are available
for your use:</p>

<ol>
    <li>Visual Basic</li>
    <li>Visual C++</li>
    <li>Visual J++</li>
    <li>FrontPage 97</li>
    <li>Publisher 97</li>
    <li>Fortran PowerStation</li>
    <li>Office 95 Pro</li>
    <li>SQL Server</li>
    <li>BackOffice</li>
    <li>Visual Test</li>
    <li>Visual Source Safe</li>
</ol>

<p>You will be expected to manage the projects using Microsoft
Project 95. Your presentations will be made to the clients using
PowerPoint.</p>

<p>This software was made available through a Microsoft Academic
Cooperative Grant.. </p>

<p>The grant site is: <a href="http://msdeved.isu.edu/ms"
target="http://msdeved.isu.edu/ms">http://msdeved.isu.edu/ms</a></p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
