<p>Quizzes may occur at any time. There will be no make-up for
these. I expect all written work to be Emailed to me and posted
on the class web page.</p>

<p>&nbsp;<b>Research Paper:</b> </p>

<p>The research paper topic will be established by agreement with
the professor. The paper will should contain original research
components. I expect you to submit it for presentation or
publication in some regional or national forum. It is anticipated
that CS majors will focus on more technical issues while CIS
majors will focus on the more managerial topics. All papers will
reflect a knowledge of the McCumber model.</p>

<p>&nbsp;<b>Lectures</b></p>

<p>In general the U.S. Government will be used as the information
security model. This is generalizable to the needs of the private
sector. Early lectures in the course will emphasize the
philosophy, legal and policy issues associated with security and
privacy. This will be followed by sections on Security History,
Access controls, Viruses, Planning, Administration,
Communication, Encryption, Networks, and Physical security.</p>

<p>&nbsp;<b>Text Book:</b> </p>

<p>There are three texts for the course.</p>

<ol>
    <li>Information Security Modules (Green Book) Free</li>
    <li>Computer Security Basics, Russel and Gangemi ~$30.00</li>
    <li>CDROM Encyclopedia of Information and Security Terms.
        When available ~ $5.00</li>
</ol>

<p><b>Additional Readings</b></p>

<ol>
    <li>Machivelli, <i>The Prince</i> </li>
    <li>Dickens, <i>Hard Times</i> </li>
    <li>Snow, <i>The Two Cultures</i></li>
    <li>Stoll, <i>The Cuckoos&#146; Egg</i></li>
</ol>

