<BR>


<P>

<font size=2>
<h2>Eyes on the Prize</h2>


<hr>
William Spain<br>
10/28/96<br>
<p>
Computerworld's 1996 Skills Survey will be published November 18. This 
is the first in a series of exclusive online previews. 
<hr>

<p>
From Atlanta to Dallas to Phoenix, the high demand for Visual Basic 
skills shows no signs of slowing. 
Salary premiums for permanent Visual Basic workers range from 3% to 16%, 
depending on the region and the nature of the work. 
"A lot of the skills are transferable. If you know Visual Basic, [it 
will be easier] to use PowerBuilder or some other visual programming 
language. It's a good item to have on a resume." <br>
-- John Kile,
<p>
Eli Lilly & Co. <br>
There seem to be only two constants in the information systems job 
market: The demand for skilled workers far outstrips the supply, and 
what is hot today may be frozen next week. 
<p>
The trick for IS professionals is to stay on top of the career 
opportunities for various technology skills, and to invest in the ones 
that are right for their portfolios. One skill that has been in much 
demand is Visual Basic and, according to a forthcoming Computerworld 
survey of IS hiring managers, it will remain so for the immediate 
future. In fact, those managers say it will be the most sought-after 
development skill of all. What follows is some information on how to 
build your VB skills, what they're worth and where they might be going 
in the future. 
<h3>By popular demand </h3>
<p>
Demand for every IS skill is increasing at an exponential rate, and 
Visual Basic is right on the leading edge. 
<p>
From Atlanta to Dallas to Phoenix, the high demand for Visual Basic 
skills shows no signs of slowing. So says Shannon Brandon, director of 
professional services division at Matrix Resources, Inc, a recruiter and 
consultancy with offices in the South and Southwest. Indeed, 
Computerworld's upcoming annual skills survey (to be published Nov. 18) 
finds it will be the most hired-for development tool next year. 
<p>
"We're seeing it all across the board -- everything from manufacturing 
to banking to service organizations," says Brandon. "It's probably the 
most prevalent requirement we get from a development tool standpoint." 
<p>
Visual Basic skills top the most wanted list on the East Coast and 
throughout the industrial Midwest, says Jack DeTurk, president of DP Job 
Works, an Indianapolis-based recruiter. 
<p>
As DeTurk sees it, IS professionals with Visual Basic skills can land 
jobs in everything from manufacturing applications to account and 
financial applications.

<p>
Source: Computerworld's 1996 skills survey, to be published Nov. 18
<p>
It pays (well!) to know Visual Basic
<p>

<h4>IS pros with Visual Basic skills command top salary premiums</h4>

<TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TH>REGION</TH> <TH>PERMANENT STAFF MEMBER CONTRACT</TH><TH>CONSULTANT</TH></TR>
<TR><TD>New England</TD><TD><CENTER>7%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>6%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Middle Atlantic</TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>10%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>East North Atlantic</TD><TD><CENTER>3%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>West North Atlantic</TD><TD><CENTER>7%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>South Atlantic</TD><TD><CENTER>6%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>10%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>East South Central</TD><TD><CENTER>10%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>NA</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>West South Central</TD><TD><CENTER>16%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>18%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Mountain</TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>6%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Pacific</TD><TD><CENTER>4%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Total</TD><TD><CENTER>6%</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
Shows what you know! 
<p>
Demand is increasing because applications are easier to put together in 
Visual Basic. Mastering this skill shows that you've got a solid 
background in visual programming. 
<p>
Part of the reason for the sustained high demand for Visual Basic, says 
John Kile, a systems analyst involved in hiring for Eli Lilly & Co., is 
its ease of use and versatility. 
<p>
"A lot of the skills are transferable. If you know Visual Basic, [it 
will be easier] to use PowerBuilder or some other visual programming 
language. It's a good item to have on a resume." 
<p>
Peggy Martinus, Chicago branch manger for consultants Greenbrier & 
Russel, believes that acquiring Visual Basic skills is definitely a good 
career move. "Some companies only use Microsoft skills," he says. "In 
general, knowing any GUI tool is an advantage."

<h3>Playing this game </h3>

Of the development tool skill sets, probably the highest-paying are 
Visual C++, Visual Basic and Powerbuilder. 
<p>
Investing in Visual Basic can certainly show dividends in your weekly 
paycheck, says Brandon. "Visual Basic may not be the highest paid of the 
three, but it's right up there close to it." 
<p>
Computerworld's forthcoming annual skills survey (to be published Nov. 
18) reveals that salary premiums for permanent Visual Basic workers 
range from 3% to 16%, depending on the region and the nature of the 
work. 
<p>
That premium may not come directly from an employer, however. There 
appears to be an increasing trend for companies to go outside their own 
ranks to fill their needs for VB skills. Contract consultants, according 
to the Computerworld survey, can command salary premiums of 5% to 18%. 
<p>
"As outsourcing continues to develop, the compensation level for what we 
like to call permanent employees probably gets pretty close to a 
standstill," says DeTurk. "Contracting inevitably drives internal 
salaries and wage increases down."
Source: Computerworld's 1996 skills survey, to be published Nov. 18

<h3>Tops in it's field</h3>

IS managers say Visual Basic will be their most sought-after development 
tool in 1997. The percentage that will hire for the skill are:REGION 
PLAN TO HIRE New England 38% Middle Atlantic 20% East North Atlantic 27% 
West North Atlantic 32% South Atlantic 20% East South Central 22% West 
South Central 20% Mountain 18% Pacific 26% Total 24%  
<p>
There seems to be almost as many ways to come by Visual Basic skills as 
there are applications for them, from home study to on-the-job 
experience to formal classroom endeavors. 
Easy to come by 
<p>
Visual Basic is a tool that a lot people can pick up on their own. 
Individual programmers can buy the tool and it's not expensive. 
<p>
There seems to be almost as many ways to come by Visual Basic skills as 
there are applications for them, from home study to on-the-job 
experience to formal classroom endeavors. 
<p>
Martinus points out that while employers will often foot the bill for 
training, even when they don't "it certainly isn't a hard class to come 
by." 
<p>
Whether VB is learned on the job, by the book or in an academic setting, 
it is clear that any investment of time or money will pay for itself in 
short order, a fact that recent IS grads seem to have realized. 
<p>
Brandon says most of his Visual Basic people are younger. "We don't see 
that many mainframers moving over. In general, our primary candidate 
base is [people who] just came out of school." 
Seeing the future 
<p>
Right now, the short-term demand is pretty hot. It is definitely still a 
tool of choice. But in three years, even two years, who knows? 
<p>
Bearing in mind the aforementioned constants of the IS world, it is 
difficult to tell what the long-term appetite for Visual Basic will be. 
The near future is easier since many VB projects are already under way, 
and companies with large investments in a particular tool are likely to 
stick with it, if for no other reason than to save face. 
<p>
Brandon is confident. "We don't see demand slowing down anytime soon," 
he says. And marketing is sure to play a role in Visual Basic's future. 
"After all," says Brandon, "having the Microsoft name tagged onto it 
doesn't hurt."
<p>
<hr>
<p>
Spain is a freelance writer in Chicago




</font>

<P>
