<HTML>
<TITLE>ISS Assessment Activities</TITLE>
<H2><A HREF="iss.html">International Security and Space Program</A></H2>
<P>
<P>
<HR>
<H3><B>Assessments in Progress:</B></H3>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#counter">Countering Proliferated Weapons of Mass Destruction (R)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#support">International Peace Support Operations (R)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#altlaunch">Assessing Future Space Launch Industry Alternatives (R)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#guns">Technologies for Tracking Ammunition and for Controlling the Inadvertent 
Use of Handguns (R)</A>
<BR>
<A HREF="#safety">Handgun Safety</A>
<BR>
<A HREF="#track">Tracking Handgun Ammunition</A>
<LI><A HREF="#model">Defense Modeling and Simulation (R)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#mass">Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction (R)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#civmil">Assessing the Potential Integration of Defense and Civilian Technology 
and Manufacturing (R)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#direct">Director-Approved Special Responses</A>
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<HR><H3><A NAME="counter">Countering Proliferated Weapons of Mass Destruction (R)</A></H3>
<P>Top officials in both Congress and the Executive Branch have identified 
the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction as one of the most, 
if not the most, important security threat facing the United States 
and the rest of the international community in the post-Cold War 
era. An urgent priority of U.S. foreign policy is to prevent the 
further spread of nuclear, chemical, or biological weapons and, in 
some cases, to cause those possessing such weapons to give them up. 
Nevertheless, prudent military planners must prepare for the contingency 
that U.S. military forces may confront adversaries armed with these 
weapons. OTA proposes to assess the technological components of three 
stages of response to proliferation: counterforce, active defense, 
and passive defense. To evaluate the prospects for success in each 
stage, three questions must be addressed:
<UL>
<P><LI>Requirements--what conditions must be met to accomplish the task?
<P><LI>Potential--how might the technology options under consideration 
meet the requirements?
<P><LI>Limitations--what inherent problems and uncertainties are likely 
to constrain success?
</UL>
<P>The OTA assessment has the goal of helping Congress to understand 
the potential, the limitations, and the implications of the countering 
technologies that it is being asked to fund. With such understanding, 
it can make more informed decisions about how to allocate national 
resources toward ameliorating the proliferation threat.
<P>Project Directors: Gerald Epstein 228-6428
<P>Thomas Karas 228-6430
<P>Estimated publication date: Spring 1996.
<P>Associated publication: "Detecting Nuclear Facilities Through 
Environmental Samples" (BP), Summer 1995.
<P>Requested by: House Committee on Armed Services
<BR>Senate Committee on Governmental Affairs
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="support">International Peace Support Operations (R</A>)</H3>
<P>International peace support operations and U.S. involvement in 
them have increased greatly since the end of the Cold War. New areas 
of operation (added to old ones, such as Cyprus, the Sinai, the Golan 
Heights) have included Bosnia, Somalia, Angola, and a police action 
(rather than peacekeeping operation) to reverse the results of aggression 
in Kuwaitthe first such case since Korea in 1950.
<P>Operations include peacekeepingundertaken with a cease-fire in 
place and aimed at permitting negotiations (e.g., Cyprus)peace enforcementdone 
without a workable cease-fire or without the agreement of all parties 
involved (e.g., Somalia, Liberia)and police actions, in which an 
intervention force deals with an aggressor. Each type of activity 
will have its own technical requirements: technological, operational, 
and doctrinal. In addition to their other military requirements, 
peace support operations involving more than one nation have serious 
command and control issues to face.
<P>As recent events have shown, few of these issues have been well 
worked out; resolving them will be necessary if U.S. forces are to 
participate with maximum effectiveness and minimum risk. The study 
will examine the inter-operability of U.S. forces with those of other 
countries, including command and control issues and the variability 
of equipment and training among the different nations participating 
in a mixed force. To this end, the study will draw both on recent 
examples, including the integration of forces in NATO, and on general 
analyses. Of particular interest will be the future of U.N. command 
and control structures, which are currently evolving. This work will 
also discuss and analyze doctrines and tactics required for various 
types of peacekeeping. The study will also address training requirements 
for peace support activities. Further, the assessment will examine 
technical requirements for the various kinds of peace support operations 
that U.S. troops may face, including less-than-lethal weapons, remote 
sensing, mine detection systems, and C3I technology.
<P>Project Director: Anthony Fainberg 228-6429.
<P>Estimated publication date: Summer 1996.
<P>Associated publication: "Possible Applications of Less-Than-Lethal 
Weapons in Peace Support Operations" (BP), Fall 1995. 
<P>Requested by: House Committee on Armed Services
<BR>Senate Committee on Armed Services
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="altlaunch">Assessing Future Space Launch Industry Alternatives (R)</A></H3>
<P>For nearly four decades, the space launch industry has been one 
of the main elements of the U.S. high technology strategy. It has 
been used to demonstrate U.S. technological prowess; assure the nations 
strategic nuclear deterrent; supply policymakers with intelligence, 
geodesy, weather, navigation, and other vital information; generate 
and spin-off new technologies in a number of fields; and increasingly 
support space-oriented industrial growth, particularly in telecommunications. 
Once solidly based, its future is now very unclear. The U.S. space 
launch industry faces the challenge of having to adjust both to the 
political and economic realignments brought on by the end of the 
Cold War and to stiff competition from foreign launch systems, much 
of it subsidized. Already, the one-time American monopoly on commercial 
launch services has fallen to a 30-percent market share. This is 
not only a showcaseindustry involving many high-skilled jobs, but 
also one entwined with other technology-intensive industries that 
depend on access to space or technologies developed for space. It 
is also vital to future intelligence and defense missions. The response 
of government and industry to these challenges in the near-term will 
affect the health of the space launch and aerospace industry for 
decades to come. Building on OTAs previous work on the defense industry 
and space policy, and on recent NASA and DOD studies of space transportation, 
this study will:
<UL>
<P><LI>Estimate the U.S. governments space launch and ballistic missile 
modernization needs for the next two decades and analyze the implications 
for the launch industry.
<P><LI>Estimate commercial markets and identify factors likely to influence 
their growth.
<P><LI>Assess alternative government policies regarding the development, 
production, and operations of domestic space launch vehicles.
<P><LI>Analyze the economic and technological implications for the space 
launch industry of the expected defense industry contraction and 
consolidation.
<P><LI>Evaluate foreign launch industries and contrast their technical 
capabilities with U.S. industry.
<P><LI>Assess the technology base for developing the next generation 
of space-launchers and ballistic missiles, including the state of 
government research laboratories.
</UL>
<P>Project Director: Christopher Waychoff 228-6447.
<P>Estimated publication date: Summer 1996.
<P>Associated publication: "National Space Transportation Implementation 
Plan" (BP), Spring 1995.
<P>Requested by: House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="guns">Technologies for Tracking Ammunition and for Controlling the Inadvertent Use of Handguns (R)</A></H3>
<P>Residents throughout the United States are increasingly concerned 
about an epidemicof violence. The misuse of handgunsincluding accidents 
involving handguns and the use of handguns in crimesis an important 
source of this concern. Accidents involving children and guns are 
particularly unsettling. This assessment will examine technological 
aspects of potential measures to: 1) facilitate the identification 
and apprehension of those who have committed criminal acts of violence 
using handguns and 2) reduce handgun accidents, especially among 
children.
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="safety">Handgun Safety</A></H3>
<P>Handguns are intended to remain quiescent unless fired intentionally. 
However, children and adults who are not trained in the proper handling 
and ownership of firearms are a source of gun accidents. Inadvertent 
firings occur for a number of reasons, including such operator errors 
as failing to realize a gun is loaded or failing to handle a loaded 
gun in a proper manner.
<P>Many ideas have been proposed to reduce gun accidents. These often 
take the form of devices to force the use of a gun to become a more 
deliberate act and include such things as trigger locks, magazine 
safety devices, and load indicators. Ideas to make firearms less 
likely to be used by a child include special fire-safety devices 
and safer storage; for example, bedside lock boxes.
<P>This section of the assessment will survey such ideas, analyze 
their advantages and disadvantages, and assess their likely effectiveness. 
Issues related to the cost of implementation and market acceptability 
will also be addressed. In addition, OTA will survey programs to 
educate adults and children in the proper handling and ownership 
of firearms and assess their effectiveness.

<HR><H3><A NAME="track">Tracking Handgun Ammunition</A></H3>
<P>This part of the assessment will examine the feasibility of using 
new chemical or physical marking techniques to: 1) assist law enforcement 
officers in establishing links between a discharged handgun and a 
particular bullet; 2) assist law enforcement officers in tracing 
ammunition used in crimes.
<P>The effectiveness of ammunition tracking measures would be reduced 
if certain ammunition were difficult to trace, if ammunition casing 
were easily reused, or if it were possible to stockpile unmarked 
ammunition in significant quantities. OTA will provide the requesters 
with information on these questions.  In addition, OTA will determine 
if handgun ammunition has a shelf life,and, if so, what the likely 
consequences would be for using out-of-date ammunition.
<P>OTA will also report on typical consumer gun and ammunition buying 
patterns and the technical performance of modern handgun ammunition. 
This will include a summary of results obtained from the handgun 
ammunition/wound ballistics tests most recently conducted by the 
Firearms Training Unit of the Federal Bureau of Investigation. Finally, 
OTA will provide a brief analysis of computerized ballistic comparison 
systems and discuss their utility in linking ammunition to firearms. 
This analysis will include systems now in use by the FBI and the 
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms.
<P>
<P>Project Director: Arthur Charo 228-6445.
<P>Estimated publication date: Spring 1995.
<P>Requested by: Senate Committee on Finance
<BR>Technology Assessment Board
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="model">Defense Modeling and Simulation (R)</A></H3>
<P>Over the past three decades, the Department of Defense has relied 
increasingly on computer-based models of combat to support procurement 
and force structure decisions, and on simulations to train commanders 
and equipment operators. Controversy has surrounded these efforts, 
primarily on the basis thatas approximations of realitythey have 
the potential to introduce misleading unreality into decision-making 
and training. In the past few years, improvements in computing technology 
and data acquisition have made it possible to base models and simulations 
on much more complete and detailed data, greatly reducing a source 
of error and expanding the potential of these technologies. For example, 
models using detailed data about actual terrain can enable service 
people to train under the same conditions troops will encounter in 
combat, using simulators loaded with the same data as will go into 
the guidance systems of real weapons. Major changes that have accompanied 
the end of the cold warreductions in defense spending and the introduction 
of much greater uncertainty into planning scenarioshave increased 
the potential value of being able to solve problems through modeling 
and simulation rather than by more costly methods.
<P>Many technological problems remain to be solved, how- ever, before 
the full potential of this emerging technology can be realized. Over 
the next several years, Congress will be asked to fund development 
and application of these technologies, and to endorse major decisions 
made based on their use. This assessment will help Congress understand 
the potential of the technology as well as the remaining problems. 
It will: 1) explain the technology and how it has developed; 2) assess 
the current state-of-the-art and potential for progress; 3) present 
a synopsis of what has been learned from several decades of efforts 
in modeling, simulation, and analysis; and 4) analyze the implications 
and impediments to realizing them. It will help Congress to  understand 
the technology and its implications and issues raised by its development 
and use, and identify and choose among options for dealing with those 
issues.
<P>
<P>Project Director: Brian McCue 228-6442.
<P>Estimated publication date: Summer 1995.
<P>Associated publications: "Distributed Interactive Simulation" 
(BP), Spring 1995.
<BR>"History of Federally Funded Research and Development Centers" 
(BP), Spring 1995.
<BR><A HREF = "ftp://bilbo.isu.edu/pub/ota/vr.military/hypertext/contents.htm">"Virtual Reality and Technologies for Combat Simulation"</A> (BP), 
published September 1994.
<P>Requested by: House Committee on Armed Services
<BR>Senate Committee on Armed Services
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="mass">Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction (R)</A></H3>
<P>The abatement of the strategic competition between the United 
States and the Soviet Union, the Gulf War, and the dissolution of 
the U.S.S.R. have all brought the issue of the proliferation of weapons 
of mass destruction into the forefront of national security planning. 
Such weapons, which can range from hundreds to millions of times 
more deadly than conventional weapons of the same size, pose a serious 
challenge to the United States. In addition to the acknowledged nuclear 
powers, three other states almost certainly either possess nuclear 
weapons or could produce them on short notice. Several more may be 
making efforts to acquire them. Some twenty countries may be seeking 
to produce chemical weapons; ten or so may be pursuing biological 
ones. Even if they lack the means to attack the United States directly, 
states possessing these weapons threaten U.S. allies and U.S. vital 
interests. Ultimately they may be able to strike the United States, 
either directly or via terrorist organizations. The risks of conflict 
will intensify if nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons spread 
around the world, falling under the control of unstable governments, 
or of authoritarian (or even megalomaniacal) leaders not subject 
to the restraints of democratic governance or civilian control of 
the military. This assessment compares the risks posed by proliferation 
of various weapons of mass destruction, assesses the effectiveness 
of current nonproliferation policies, and formulates relevant Congressional 
policy options, including measures designed both to impede proliferation 
and to expose it.
<P>
<P>Project Director: Gerald Epstein 228-6428.
<P>Estimated publication date:
<P>Associated publications: "Nuclear Materials and the International 
Atomic Energy Agency" (R), Spring 1995.
<BR>"Proliferation Issues and the Former Soviet Union" (R), published 
September 1994.
<BR>"Export Controls and Nonproliferation Policy" (R), published May 
1994.
<BR>"Technologies Underlying Weapons of Mass Destruction" (BP), published 
January 1994.
<BR>"Proliferation of Weapons Mass Destruction: Assessing the Risks" 
(R), published September 1993.
<BR>"The Chemical Weapons Convention: Effects on the U.S. Chemical 
Industry" (BP), published August 1993. 
<P>Requested by: Senate Committee on Foreign Relations
<BR>Senate Committee on Governmental Affairs
<BR>House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="civmil">Assessing the Potential Integration of Defense and Civilian Technology and Manufacturing (R)</A></H3>
<P>The dissolution of the Soviet Union has dramatically changed the 
military threat to the United States. However, the Nation will continue 
to face future national security challenges. Major changes in world 
politics, the U.S. and global economy, and high technology industry 
are prompting the U.S. to pursue new strategies to ensure that a 
sufficient defense technology and industrial base is available in 
the future. One of the most widely discussed alternatives is increased 
integration of the civilian and defense technology and industrial 
bases. The national security objectives of such integration include: 
reducing total costs of military equipment, gaining greater access 
to advanced technology, increasing the two-way technology flow between 
the defense and civilian sectors, and broadening the defense base 
by increasing the number of potential defense suppliers. Such integration 
might also promote international competitiveness of U.S. industry 
in general. While the idea of increased civil-military integration 
is widely supported, there is a perception that actual implementation 
has been slow. Similarly, while there has been much discussion of 
the advantages of greater integration and of barriers to such integration, 
there has been relatively little hard analysis of specific opportunities 
to exploit civil sector technology and the implications of such exploitation. 
The relatively slow acceptance of greater integration has resulted 
in considerable frustration both in Congress and within the defense 
community.
<P>This assessment will 1) provide Congress a better understanding 
of the current level of integration, 2) identify characteristics 
of specific technology and industrial sectors that lend themselves 
to integration and those in which integration appears difficult, 
3) assess the implications of integration in specific cases, and 
4) provide Congress some options to support the objective of increased 
civil-military integration.
<P>
<P>Project Director: Jack Nunn 228-6446.
<P>Estimated publication date: Published September 1994.
<P>Associated publication: "Case Studies: Assessing Potential Integration 
of Defense and Civilian Technology and Manufacturing" (BP), Winter 
1995.
<P>Requested by: Senate Committee on Armed Services, and its Subcommittee 
on Defense Industry and Technology
<BR>House Committee on Armed Services
<P>

<HR><H3><A NAME="direct">Director-Approved Special Responses</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI>Civil and Military Integration in the Chinese and Japanese Industry 
(BP)
<BR>Study Director: Jack Nunn 228-6446
<BR>Estimated publication date: Winter 1995<P>
<LI>U.S. Russian Space Cooperation (BP)
<BR>Study Director: Ray Williamson 228-6448
<BR>Estimated publication date: Summer 1995
</UL>

