<title>_ACCOUNTING 323, Intermediate Accounting I</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#C0C0C0">
<h2 align=center>ACCOUNTING 323, Intermediate Accounting I </h2>
<h3 align=center>Section 01, Fall 1996 </h3>
<h3 align=center>CLASS POLICIES </h3>
<h3>COURSE</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>ACCT 323, Section 01, 8:00am-9:15am, TTh, BA 212 </p>
<p>ACCT 323, Section 02, 9:30am-10:45am, TTh, BA </p>
</blockquote>
<h3>PROFESSOR</h3>
<ul>
<li>Lela D. Pumphrey Phone: 236-4292 </li>
<li>ISU Home Page </li>
<li>E-Mail: pumplela@ba.isu.edu </li>
<li>Office: Room 528, Business Administration Building </li>
<li>Office Hours: 9:00am-11:30am and 1:00-5:00pm W; <br>
2:30pm-5:00pm, TTh; Other times by appointment </li>
</ul>
<h3>REQUIRED MATERIALS</h3>
<ul>
<li>Intermediate Accounting, 8th Edition, Kieso &amp; Weygandt </li>
<li>Intermediate Accounting Computer Assisted Practice Set* </li>
</ul>
<h3>OPTIONAL MATERIAL</h3>
<ul>
<li>Accounting Standards, Current Text or any other GAAP Guide </li>
</ul>
<h3>COURSE OBJECTIVES</h3>
<p>Intermediate accounting is truly the beginning of your accounting career. It may well be the most 
important accounting course you take in your undergraduate curriculum because it presents the 
foundation on which all accounting decisions are made. Accounting has both a theoretical/conceptual 
basis and a practical/issue-oriented basis. You will be exposed to both theory and practice in 
Intermediate Accounting. Specific course goals or objectives are as follows. </p>
<ol>
<li>To help students gain a deeper understanding of the foundations, concepts, and standards 
underlying accounting practices and techniques. (Theory) </li>
<li>To help students gain a deeper understanding of the knowledge and skills used in financial 
accounting. (Practice) </li>
<li>To help students develop analytical skills, logical thinking abilities, oral presentations skills, and 
written communication skills. (Please read the articles &quot;Good Writing Counts&quot; and &quot;Some 
Thoughts on the Uniform CPA Examination.&quot;) </li>
<li>To help students develop interpersonal skills, including the ability to work effectively with 
others. </li>
<li>To help students develop the skills and knowledge base necessary to successfully complete 
various professional examinations. </li>
</ol>
<h3>ACCOUNTING PROGRAM OBJECTIVES</h3>
<p>The objectives of the accounting program at Idaho State University are spelled out in a &quot;Message to 
Accounting Students&quot; which is available through the office of the chairman of the Accounting 
Department. </p>
<p>*The practice set is not yet available in the bookstore. </p>
<h3>GRADING</h3>
<p>Because this course is the beginning of your accounting career, it has a variety of objectives. The 
course-specific objectives are presented in a preceding section of this Statement of Class Policies. 
The overall objectives of the accounting program are stated in a separate letter to accounting 
students. Because of the many course-specific and program objectives, grading in this class is much 
more than a quantitative analysis. Grades on exams and other class projects will most certainly be a 
determinate in the final course grade, but the instructor's professional judgment of your success in 
meeting course and program objectives will also be a determinate. Please remember that the overall 
grade in this course will be the considered opinion of the instructor with many variables taken into 
account. </p>
<p>To assist you in judging your performance on specific class examinations and assignments, the 
following schedule of possible points and a tentative numeric interpretation of those points is 
presented. Please remember that this schedule is for your benefit only. The overall grade in this 
course will take into account your professional demeanor and your progress as a professional. </p>
<table border=1>
<tr><td valign=top></td><th valign=top><b>Possible Points</b></th><th valign=top colspan=2><b>Interpretation</b></th></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Exam I </td><td align=right valign=top>100 points</td><td valign=top>90% -100% = A</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Exam II </td><td align=right valign=top>100 points</td><td valign=top>80% - 89% = B</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Exam III </td><td align=right valign=top>100 points</td><td valign=top>70% - 79% = C</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Final </td><td align=right valign=top>125 points</td><td valign=top>60% - 69% = D</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Written Assignments</td><td align=right valign=top>60 points</td><td valign=top>Below 60% = F</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Practice Set</td><td align=right valign=top>50 points</td><td valign=top></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Homework/Quiz</td><td align=right valign=top>40 points</td><td valign=top></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>Total</td><td align=center valign=top>575</td><td valign=top></td></tr>
</table>
<p>I do not post grades at the end of the semester, nor do I give grades over the telephone. You may 
leave with me a stamped, self-addressed envelope which will be used to send you your final grade. </p>
<h3>HOMEWORK/QUIZ POINTS AND CLASS PARTICIPATION</h3>
<p>Classroom attendance and advance preparation are expected. On the first day a chapter is assigned 
you are expected to have read the chapter before class. I may not lecture on the textbook directly 
since you are capable of reading it. On the dates assigned, you are expected to have the assigned 
problems completed (or at least significantly attempted) before class. We may use the assigned 
problems/questions as the basis for class discussion. Quizzes/homework points will consist of points 
for homework which will be collected on a random basis and/or problems assigned to be worked in 
class. If a problem is collected for a homework grade or a quiz is given unannounced and you are not 
present, you MAY NOT make up the points. </p>
<h3>EXAMS</h3>
<p>Unless your absence is excused in advance, missed exams cannot be made up! They will be 
recorded as a zero. If there are circumstances which the instructor feels warrants such action, exams 
may be taken early. </p>
<h3>WRITTEN ASSIGNMENTS</h3>
<p>Because accounting professionals are expected to communicate their thoughts and problem analysis 
in a variety of written forms, this course will require written papers on assigned topics. These papers 
are to be SHORT, executive-type summaries of the assigned material. The papers are to be created 
in a WordPerfect file and are to be transmitted via e-mail. </p>
<p>An Executive Summary is generally a &#147;paraphrased&#148; summary of the required reading material 
emphasizing the most important points of the material. Generally, SHORT shall mean three pages or 
less (but no more). In addition to being graded on content, your papers will be graded on grammar, 
sentence structure, and organization. Part of the assignment requires that you identify the important 
points in the reading material and include only the important points in your summary. </p>
<p>If you have trouble with this assignment, I suggest that you utilize the ISU writing lab. </p>
<h3>PRACTICE SET</h3>
<p>The practice set is to be an independent project to help you review the entire accounting cycle. 
Independent does not mean that you cannot confer with your classmates, but it does mean that you 
cannot copy your classmates. Please reread the section of the &quot;Message to Accounting Students&quot; 
which deals with ethics and professionalism. </p>
<h3>PROFESSIONAL ORGANIZATIONS</h3>
<p>During much of your professional career you will be expected to participate in professional 
organizations and continuing professional education. You are encouraged to begin this activity in 
college. Participation in the Accounting Club/Beta Alpha Psi is one, but not the only, way to 
demonstrate such participation. </p>
<h3>ACADEMIC DISHONESTY</h3>
<p>If, in my opinion, you have given or received unauthorized aid on an examination or outside project, 
you will receive a grade of zero on that exam or project. If the infraction warrants such action, your 
conduct will be reported to the appropriate university officials. </p>
<h3>USE OF TECHNOLOGY</h3>
<p>In this course you will be required to make extensive use of modern technology for communication. 
Your papers will be created in a computer word-processing package and submitted, as an attached 
file, via electronic mail. Your syllabus and class policies will be available on the ISU COB Home 
Page. I will use both the Home Page and electronic mail to communicate with you during the 
semester and you will be expected to check each regularly for communications. </p>
</body>

