<h2 align=center>ACCOUNTING 323, Intermediate Accounting I</h2>
<h2 align=center>Sections 01 and 92, Fall 1996</h2>
<h3 align=center>EXPANDED CLASS ASSIGNMENTS</h3>
<p><tt>----------------------------------------------------------------</tt> </p>
<h3>Introduction to Financial Accounting and Reporting</h3>
<p><tt>The purpose is to introduce students to the environment and role of 
financial accounting and reporting in a market-driven economy and to the 
nature of financial reporting. The standard setting process and the 
historical development of current financial reporting will also be 
discussed.</tt> </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 1 </p>
<h3>The Theoretical Structure of Financial Accounting and Reporting</h3>
<p>The purpose is to introduce students to the theoretical structure of financial accounting and reporting 
including: (1) the environmental assumptions, (2) the objectives of financial reporting, (3) the 
qualitative characteristics of useful accounting information, (4) the elements of financial statements, 
(5) the recognition and measurement principles for elements of financial statements, (6) the role of 
adequate disclosure, and (7) methods of financial statement presentation. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 2 </p>
<p align=right>Q-2, Q-3, Q-5, Q-10, Q-17, Q-23, Q-26 </p>
<h3>Review of the Accounting Process</h3>
<p>The purpose is to review the accounting cycle and basic bookkeeping. The student will analyze 
transactions, record entries in the journal, post to the ledger, prepare a trial balance, make adjusting 
entries, and prepare financial statements. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 3 </p>
<p align=right>E3-2, E3-6, E3-13, E3-16 </p>
<p align=right>E3-18*, E3-22, E3-29 </p>
<h3>The Income Statement</h3>
<p>The purpose is to introduce various types of income statements, to gain an understanding of the 
classifications on the income statement, and to understand the impact of net income/net loss on the 
owners'/stockholders' equity. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 4 </p>
<p align=right>E4-5*, E4-6* </p>
<p align=right>E4-12, E4-15, E4-17, E4-10 </p>
<h3>The Balance Sheet </h3>
<p>The purpose is to introduce the classifications and valuations used in the balance sheet as well as the 
required disclosures. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 5 </p>
<p align=right>Q5-1, Q5-4, E5-1, E5-5*, E5-12 </p>
<h3>The Statement of Cash Flows</h3>
<p>The purpose is to introduce the statement of cash flows, with an emphasis on its usefulness and its 
preparation. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 5 </p>
<p align=right>Q5-27, E5-13, E5-16* </p>
<h3>Time Value of Money</h3>
<p>The purpose is to introduce the concept of the time value of money and its application to various 
accounting measurements. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 6 </p>
<p align=right>E6-1, E6-2, E6-3, E6-6, E6-10 </p>
<p align=right>E6-12, E6-13, E6-14, E6-15, E6-16 </p>
<h3>Cash</h3>
<p>The purpose is to learn the appropriate measurement and reporting requirements for cash. In 
addition, both ordinary and four-column bank reconciliations will be introduced. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 7 </p>
<p align=right>Q1-1, Q7-5, E7-1, E7-3, E7-5, P7-18 </p>
<h3>Receivables</h3>
<p>The purpose is to learn the appropriate measurement and reporting requirements for receivables. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 7 </p>
<p align=right>Q7-8, Q7-9, E7-9, E7-11, E7-16, E7-17, E7-19, P7-17 </p>
<h3>Inventories--Determining Cost and Using Cost Flow Assumptions</h3>
<p>The purpose is to learn the appropriate measurement and reporting requirements for inventories. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 8 </p>
<p align=right>Q8-8, E8-1, E8-6, E8-7, E8-16 </p>
<p align=right>E8-23, E8-27, P8-14 </p>
<h3>Inventories--Additional Valuation Problems</h3>
<p>The purpose is to learn several accepted methods of valuing inventory that are vary from the simple 
cost flow assumptions. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 9 </p>
<p align=right>Q9-2, Q9-4, Q9-8, E9-2, E9-7, E9-9, E9-10 </p>
<p align=right>E9-11, E9-12 E9-21, E9-23, E9-25 </p>
<h3>Property, Plant and Equipment</h3>
<p>The purpose is to describe characteristics of property, plant, and equipment and to identify the costs 
that are included in the initial valuation of property, plant, and equipment. Costs associated with 
property, plant, and equipment that are incurred subsequent to acquisition are also discussed. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 10 </p>
<p align=right>E10-1, E10-2, E10-3, E10-7, E10-9, E10-14 </p>
<p align=right>E10-16, E10-17, E10-18, E10-19, E10-23 </p>
<h3>Depreciation and Depletion</h3>
<p>The purpose is explain the concept of depreciation and to introduce those depreciation methods that 
are acceptable under GAAP. Income tax &quot;depreciation&quot; will also be discussed. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 11 </p>
<p align=right>Q11-1, Q11-3, Q11-21, E11-1*, E11-8, E11-13, E11-14 </p>
<p align=right>E11-18, E11-21, E11-23, E11-24, E11-26 </p>
<h3>Intangible Assets</h3>
<p>The purpose is to describe the characteristics of intangible assets and the accounting and financial 
reporting issues associated with intangible assets. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 12 </p>
<p align=right>E12-1, E12-4, E12-7, E12-8, E12-9, E12-10, E12-11 </p>
<p align=right>E12-13, E12-16, E12-20, E12-21, E12-22, E12-23 </p>
<h3>Current Liabilities and Contingencies</h3>
<p>The purpose is to define current liabilities and describe how they are valued. </p>
<p align=right>Chapter 13 </p>
<p align=right>Q13-1, Q13-5, Q13-7, Q13-8, E13-1 </p>
<p align=right>E13-5, E13-8, E13-17, E13-11, E13-12, E13-13 </p>
<p>*You may do these problems by hand or on a computer using a spreadsheet package. I strongly 
recommend that you use these problems to learn how to use a spreadsheet. </p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
