<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>ACCOUNTING 456, Auditing I</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">ACCOUNTING 456, Auditing I</FONT></TT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Section 01, Spring 1997</FONT></TT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">CLASS POLICIES<BR>
</FONT></TT></CENTER>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">COURSE</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">ACCT 456, Section 01,11:00pm-12:15pm,
MW, BA 412</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">PROFESSOR</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Lela D. Pumphrey Phone: 236-4292</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">E-Mail: pumplela@ba.isu.edu</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Office: Room 528, Business Administration
Building</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Office Hours: 9:00am-11:00am and 1:30-5:00pm
T;</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">1:30pm-5:00pm, MW; Other times by appointment
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">REQUIRED MATERIALS</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">Auditing, 8th Edition</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Courier">,
Jack C. Robertson<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">OPTIONAL MATERIAL</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">Statements on Auditing Standards</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Courier">
or any other GAAS Guide <BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">COURSE OBJECTIVES</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Auditing I is the only accounting course
you take in your undergraduate curriculum that presents material
specifically related to performing the attest function. Because
a thorough understanding of generally accepted accounting principles
and financial reporting is required in order to perform a financial
statement audit, Auditing is generally one of the last courses
taken in your undergraduate program. Specific course goals or
objectives are as follows.<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">1. To help students gain a deeper understanding
of the foundations, concepts, and standards underlying auditing
practices and techniques. (Theory)</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">2. To help students gain a deeper understanding
of the practices and procedures used in financial statement auditing.
(Practice)</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">3. To help students develop analytical
skills, logical thinking abilities, oral presentations skills,
and written communication skills.</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">4. To help students develop interpersonal
skills, including the ability to work effectively with others.</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">5. To help students develop the skills
and knowledge base necessary to successfully complete various
professional examinations. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">ACCOUNTING PROGRAM OBJECTIVES</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">The objectives of the accounting program
at Idaho State University are spelled out in a &quot;Message to
Accounting Students&quot; which is available through the office
of the chairman of the Accounting Department.<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">GRADING</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Because this course is taken near the
<U>end of your undergraduate accounting program</U>, it has a
variety of objectives. The course-specific objectives are presented
in a preceding section of this Statement of Class Policies. The
overall objectives of the accounting program are stated in a separate
letter to accounting students. Because of the many course-specific
and program objectives, grading in this class is much more than
a quantitative analysis. Grades on exams and other class projects
will most certainly be a determinate in the final course grade,
but the instructor's professional judgment of your success in
meeting course and program objectives will also be a determinate.
Please remember that the overall grade in this course will be
the considered opinion of the instructor with many variables taken
into account. <BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">To assist you in judging your performance
on specific class examinations and assignments, the following
schedule of possible points and a tentative numeric interpretation
of those points is presented. Please remember that this schedule
is for your benefit only. The overall grade in this course will
take into account your professional demeanor and your progress
as a professional.<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">Possible Points</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Courier">
<U>Interpretation</U></FONT></TT>
<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Exam I</FONT></TT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">150 points</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">90%-100% = A</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Exam II</FONT></TT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">150 points</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">80%-89% = B</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Class Participation</FONT></TT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">100 points</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">70%-79% = C</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Final</FONT></TT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">150 points</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">60%-69% = D</FONT></TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Written Project</FONT></TT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">100 points</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">Below 60% = F</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Oral Presentation</FONT></TT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197><TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">50</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Courier"> points</FONT></TT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=197></TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197><TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Total</FONT></TT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">700</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=197>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=197></TD><TD WIDTH=197></TD><TD WIDTH=197></TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>

<P>

<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">I do not post grades at the end of the
semester, nor do I give grades over the telephone. You may leave
with me a stamped, self-addressed envelope which will be used
to send you your final grade.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">CLASS PARTICIPATION</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Classroom attendance and advance preparation
are expected. [THREFORE YOU ARE EXPECTED TO BE CURRENT IN YOUR
READING AND PREPARATION.] The author of the textbook is an expert
who communicates very well. I will presume that you understand
the text material unless you ask for clarification. My purpose
will be to elaborate on the authors' discussions (but not repeat
them) and to challenge you to apply what you have read. You are
responsible for reading the chapter and working end-of-chapter
material outside of class. All students will be expected to have
prepared the review checkpoints and multiple choice questions.
[THE MULTIPLE CHOICE QUESTIONS AND ONE OR MORE OF THE FOLLOWING
SHOULD BE PREPARED IN ELECTRONIC FORMAT AND INCLUDED IN YOUR NOTEBOOK--THE
REVIEW CHECKPOINTS, A CHAPTER OUTLINE, OR CHAPTER NOTES]<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">WRITING ASSIGNMENT</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Your task in this course is to develop
a professional approach to your career. To help you meet this
task, you should read the Wall Street Journal daily and various
accounting magazines monthly. AS YOU FIND PERTINENT ARTICLES,
WRITE A SYNOPSIS OF THE ARTICLE (USING COMPLETE SENTENCES, GOOD
GRAMMAR, ETC.) FOR INCLUSION IN YOUR &quot;NOTEBOOK.&quot; The
'Notebook' should be one or more computer files (created on a
computer wordprocessing package) which are then merged into one
file. Be sure to include an index for this &quot;Notebook.&quot;
The &quot;Notebook&quot; file should be submitted, via e-mail,
by the due date indicated on the class syllabus. NOTE: I DO NOT
WANT ANY PAPER. THIS IS 'PAPERLESS' EVENT.</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">EXAMS</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Unless your absence is excused in advance,
missed exams cannot be made up! They will be recorded as a zero.
If there are circumstances which the instructor feels warrants
such action, exams may be taken early. <BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">ORAL PRESENTATIONS</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">In your professional career you will
be required to communicate ideas both in writing and speaking.
To help develop verbal communication skills, each student group
will be assigned a topic [SEE THE CLASS SCHEDULE]. For these presentations,
professional dress and professional presentations (including visual
aids) are expected. </FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">Each student group will be expected to
be an expert on the topic assigned to their group. Much outside
research related to the topic is expected. [INCLUDE IN YOUR NOTEBOOK
A SYNOPSIS OF EACH ARTICLE, BOOKS, ETC., USED IN DEVELOPING YOUR
MATERIAL FOR YOUR PRESENTATION.] Each group MUST MEET WITH THE
INSTRUCTOR prior to their class presentation to discuss the topic
and the presentation material.<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">PROFESSIONAL ORGANIZATIONS</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">During much of your professional career
you will be expected to participate in professional organizations
and continuing professional education. You have been encouraged
to begin this activity in college. Participation in the Accounting
Club/Beta Alpha Psi is one, but not the only, way to demonstrate
such participation.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">ACADEMIC DISHONESTY</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">If, in my opinion, you have given or
received unauthorized aid on an examination or outside project,
you will receive a grade of zero on that exam or project. If the
infraction warrants such action, your conduct will be reported
to the appropriate university officials.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier">USE OF TECHNOLOGY</FONT></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><FONT FACE="Courier">In this course you will be required to
make extensive use of modern technology for communication. Your
notebooks will be created in a computer word-processing package
and submitted, as an attached file, via electronic mail. Also,
your assignments and other communications from me will be available
on either a Home Page on the World Wide Web or by e-mail. You
will be expected to check the electronic mail and the Home Page
regularly for messages.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></TT>
</BODY>

