<P>
<CENTER><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>ACCOUNTING 456, Auditing I</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>Section 01, Spring 1997</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>EXPANDED CLASS ASSIGNMENTS<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Overview of Auditing
<P>
The purpose is to introduce students to the concept of auditing,
in general, and to the environment and role of financial auditing
and reporting in a market-driven economy, specifically. The standard
setting process and the historical development of current financial
auditing will also be discussed.
<P>
Chapter 1
<HR>

<P>
Auditing Standards
<P>
The purpose is to introduce the standards applicable to specific
activities
<P>
Chapter 2
<HR>

<P>
Audit Reports
<P>
The purpose is to introduce students to the nature of and need
for auditor's reports as well as to introduce the types of reports
issued by independent auditors.
<P>
Chapter 3
<HR>

<P>
Audit Responsibilities and Objectives
<P>
The purpose is to introduce the objectives of a financial statement
audit and the process by which these objectives are met.
<P>
Chapter 4
<HR>

<P>
Audit Planning with Analytical Procedures, Risk, and Materiality
<P>
The purpose is to introduce the concept of audit planning and
to introduce ways to document the planning.
<P>
Chapter 5
<HR>

<P>
Internal Control
<P>
The purpose is to discuss the nature, concepts and components
of internal control and to describe the auditor's responsibilities
in relation to internal control in the audit of financial statements.
<P>
Chapter 6
<HR>

<P>
Audit Sampling
<P>
The purpose is to introduce the concept of audit sampling.
<P>
Chapter 7
<HR>

<P>
Fraud Auditing
<P>
The purpose is to introduce the techniques of auditing for fraud.
<P>
Chapter 8
<HR>

<P>
Auditing the Sales and Collection Cycle
<P>
The purpose is to learn to write and implement an audit program
so as to gather evidence related to the sales and collection cycle.
<P>
Chapter 9
<HR>

<P>
Auditing the Acquisition and Payment Cycle
<P>
The purpose is to learn to write and implement an audit program
so as to gather evidence related to the acquisition and payment
cycle.
<HR>

<P>
Chapter 10
<HR>

<P>
Auditing the Production and Payroll Cycle
<P>
The purpose is to learn to write and implement an audit program
so as to gather evidence related to the payroll and personnel
cycle.
<P>
Chapter 11
<HR>

<P>
Auditing the Financing and Investment Cycle
<P>
The purpose is to learn to write and implement an audit program
so as to gather evidence related to the financing and investment
cycle.
<P>
Chapter 12
<HR>

<P>
Completing the Audit
<P>
The purpose is to learn the additional requirements for completing
an audit including items such as (1) identifying contingent liabilities
and commitments, (2) obtaining representation letters from attorneys,
(3) identifying subsequent events, (4) determining that all necessary
disclosures are made, and (5) evaluating the results of the evidence-gathering
procedures.
<P>
Chapter 13
<HR>

<P>
Other engagements
<P>
The purpose is to become acquainted with some other types of services
that can be provided by independent accountants/auditors. These
include compilation and review services related to financial statements,
reviews of interim financial information for public companies,
and other services that provide assurances or limited assurances.
<P>
Chapter 18
<HR>

<P>
Other Types of Auditing Services
<P>
The purpose is to become familiar with internal auditing, governmental
auditing, and operational auditing. The focus will be on the similarities
and differences between these audit services and traditional audits
of financial statements.
<P>
Chapter 19
<HR>

<P>
Professional Ethics
<P>
The purpose is to discuss ethical behavior in general and to discuss
ethical behavior that is specifically applicable to independent
auditors.
<P>
Chapter 20
<HR>

<P>
Legal Liability
<P>
The purpose is to introduce the primary legal concepts concerning
auditors' legal liability to a variety of parties.
<P>
Chapter 21
<HR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
