<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Office Hours: 9:30am-11:30am,
1:30pm-5:00pm T; 1:30pm-5:00pm MW; Other times by appointment
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">REQUIRED MATERIALS</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Accounting for Governmental
and Nonprofit Entities,</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">10th Edition</FONT></SUB></U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">,
by Hay &amp; Wilson</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">CAFR for a City, County, or
School District <BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">COURSE OBJECTIVES</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">This course is the first accounting
course in which you will be exposed to an in-depth analysis of
accounting for governmental and other not-for-profit entities.
It is one step along the path of your accounting career. This
course presents the foundation on which all accounting for not-for-profit
entities is based. Accounting for these special entities has both
a theoretical/ conceptual basis and a practical, issue-oriented
basis. You will be exposed to both theory and practice in this
course. Specific course goals or objectives are as follows.<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">1. To help students gain a
deeper understanding of the foundations, concepts, and standards
underlying accounting practices and techniques in not-for-profit
entities. (Theory)</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">2. To help students gain a
deeper understanding of the knowledge and skills used in financial
accounting for not-for-profit entities. (Practice)</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">3. To help students develop
analytical skills, logical thinking abilities, oral presentations
skills, and written communication skills.</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">4. To help students develop
interpersonal skills, including the ability to work effectively
with others.</FONT></SUB></TT>
<OL>
<LI><TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">To help students develop
the skills and knowledge base necessary to successfully complete
various professional examinations.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
</OL>

<P>

<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">ACCOUNTING PROGRAM OBJECTIVES</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The objectives of the accounting
program at Idaho State University are spelled out in a &quot;Message
to Accounting Students&quot; which is available through the office
of the chairman of the Accounting Department.<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">GRADING</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Because this course is </FONT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier New">one
step in your accounting career, it has a variety of objectives.
The course-specific objectives are presented in a preceding section
of this Statement of Class Policies. The overall objectives of
the accounting program are stated in a separate letter to accounting
students. Because of the many course-specific and program objectives,
grading in this class is much more than a quantitative analysis.
Grades on exams and other class projects will most certainly be
a determinate in the final course grade, but the instructor's
professional judgment of your success in meeting course and program
objectives will also be a determinate. Please remember that the
overall grade in this course will be the considered opinion of
the instructor with many variables taken into account. <BR>
o assist you in judging your performance on specific class examinations
and assignments, the following schedule of possible points and
a tentative numeric interpretation of those points is presented.
Please remember that this schedule is for your benefit only. The
overall grade in this course will take into account your professional
demeanor and your progress as a professional.</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Possible Points</FONT></SUB></U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">
</FONT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier New">Interpretation</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Exam I 100 points 90%-100%
= A</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Exam II 100 points 80%-89%
= B</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Exam III 100 points 70%-79%
= C</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Final 125 points 60%-69% =
D</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Papers 60 points Below 60%
= F</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Project 40 points</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">CAFR Project </FONT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier New">75
points</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Total 600 points <BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">I do not post grades at the
end of the semester, nor do I give grades over the telephone.
You may leave with me a stamped, self-addressed envelope which
I will use to send you your final grade.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">CLASS PARTICIPATION AND
HOMEWORK</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Classroom attendance and advance
preparation are expected. Homework is for your benefit, not course
credit. To the extent possible, the assigned problems will be
discussed in class. Because you are upperclassmen capable of reading
the textbook, class time will usually be devoted to discussing
your individual CAFR projects or analysis of the material presented.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">EXAMS</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Unless your absence is excused
in advance, missed exams cannot be made up! They will be recorded
as a zero. If there are circumstances which the instructor feels
warrants such action, exams may be taken early.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">PAPERS</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">There are three papers assigned.
The subjects appear on the class assignment sheets. The reading
materials will be available in the library, through the reserve
desk. These papers are to be SHORT. Three pages, transmitted electronically,
are all that is expected. They are to be &quot;executive summaries.&quot;
The papers should demonstrate three things: (1) you read the assigned
material, (2) you understood the material, and (3) you can communicate
that understanding.</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">An executive summary is generally
a </FONT></SUB></TT><SUB><FONT FACE="Arial">A</FONT></SUB><TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">paraphrased</FONT></SUB></TT><SUB><FONT FACE="Arial">@</FONT></SUB><TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">
summary of the important points in the reading material. In addition
to being graded on content, your papers will be graded on grammar,
sentence structure, and organization. Part of the assignment requires
that you identify the important points in the reading material
and include only the important points in your summary. </FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">If you have trouble with this
assignment, I suggest that you utilize the ISU writing lab.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">CAFR Project</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The CAFR Project is an analysis
of an actual set of financial statements. You will be furnished
with a CAFR of a particular local government. You will be required
to write to a City of your choice (which I will approve) to receive
a CAFR for a student in the next class. </FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The purpose of the completed
report should be two-fold. First, the report should address the
particular reporting standards used by your entity and whether
or not those reporting standards are acceptable. If you find violations
of GAAP, discuss these violations in terms of what standards are
violated. (Please help me by identifying the page(s) of the CAFR
on which the error appears.) </FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Second, arrive at a decision
about the financial condition of the financial reporting entity
and/or any of its component units. Please document how you arrived
at your decision, including page references to assist the reader.
In addition, you should point out any implications of the financial
data. For example, if 75% of the structures of a school system
are over 50 years old, the logical interpretation is that a building
project is imminent. </FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">To assist you in your financial
analysis, a checklist is on reserve at the library. That should
not be your only means of analyzing the CAFR, but it should help
you.</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The paper on the CAFR should
be about 25 pages. Fifteen pages would be acceptable, if it covered
all of the relevant material. The paper should be typed in WordPerfect
format, double-spaced, and submitted electronically by the due
date. You must also submit your CAFR so that I will have it when
I grade the papers. You may have your CAFR back when I have completed
the grading.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">PROJECT</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">You should participate in a
community project of assistance to a governmental entity or non-profit
agency. For example, you may participate in a project to analyze
NFP financial statements for United Way. You should do this project
in teams. Discuss your project with me before starting the project.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">ACADEMIC DISHONESTY</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">If, in my opinion, you have
given or received unauthorized aid on an examination or outside
project, you will receive a grade of zero on that exam or project.
If the infraction warrants such action, your conduct will be reported
to the appropriate university officials.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
<P>
<TT><U><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">USE OF TECHNOLOGY</FONT></SUB></U></TT>
<P>
<TT><SUB><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">In this course you will be
required to make extensive use of modern technology for communication.
Your papers will be created in a computer word-processing package
and submitted, as an attached file, via electronic mail. Also,
your assignments and other communications from me will be available
on the ISU COB Home Page on the World Wide Web. You will be expected
to check the electronic mail and the Home Page regularly for messages.
<BR>
</FONT></SUB></TT>
</BODY>

