<TITLE>The Text Editor</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>The Text Editor</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The text editor that you will be creating in assignment #1 is similar to the Notepad in windows.  For simplicity, the menu system will have fewer options than notepad.  The following options must be present in your version of notepad.   </P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Menu System Described</P></B></FONT>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><TABLE BORDER CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=7 WIDTH=144>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>File</B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>&#9;</B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>New</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Open</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Save</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Exit</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Edit</B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Cut</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Copy</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Paste</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Search</B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Find</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="46%" VALIGN="TOP">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="54%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Replace</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P><A HREF="notepad.zip">Download Completed Notepad (NotePad.ZIP)</A></P></B></FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2><P>You may use this version of notepad as an example of the notepad assignment.  If you had difficulty with the assignment, you may want to use this version as the starting point for the command processing and printing assignments.</P>
</FONT>
<B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>New Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option sets the program back to its initial state.  That is, the text box should be cleared, the stored file name should be cleared and the system should be setup as if just started.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Open Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option should be able to open a text &quot;*.TXT&quot; or &quot;*.*&quot; file into the editing area by use of a dialog that lists drives, directories, and files.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Save Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option should be able to save the contents of the edit area to a file. if a file name is not already known to the program, this option should prompt for a file name (using the common dialog).</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Exit Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This option should end the operation of the program.  The button should execute the &quot;queryunload&quot; event of the primary form.  The &quot;queryunload&quot; event should prompt to save data if there is any text in the edit area and confirm exit.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Cut Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option should cut selected text in the edit area to the clipboard.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Copy Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option should copy selected text in the edit area to the clipboard.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Paste Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option should paste any contents of the clipboard into the edit area at the current cursor position only if the contents of the clipboard is text (not graphics).</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Find Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This menu option should display an input dialog that asks for a string to search for in the edit area.  After the text has been entered, this option should search the edit area for the specified string and highlight the first occurrence after the current cursor position or report that the &quot;Search text was not found.&quot;</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Replace Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The replace option should be similar to the find option except for the fact that the system will replace ALL occurrences of the &quot;search&quot; string with the &quot;replace&quot; string.  This function should replace all references in the entire search area.  This function should also report &quot;Search text was not found&quot; if the system was unable to find a suitable match.</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Text Edit Window</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The text editing area should have both horizontal and vertical scrollbars for the text box used to create the edit area.  The text box for the edit area should also have the &quot;multiline&quot; property set to true.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The window itself should have its &quot;windowstate&quot; property set to &quot;0 - sizeable.&quot;  This will allow the user to adjust the window at run time.  As a consequence of this, the text edit area will have to resize when the form does.  To accomplish this task, use the &quot;resize&quot; event of the form and the &quot;move&quot; method of the text box.</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Other Options (Optional)</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Any individual who would like to add additional options to this program may do so.  Examples of additional options would be something like a &quot;print&quot; option below the &quot;File&quot; menu.  Any additional features will serve as 5 points each of extra credit on the project (Maximum of 20 Points).  NOTE: all required materials must work properly before any additional features will be accepted for extra credit.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Additional optional sections could include:</P>
<P>&#9;Adding a &quot;Find Next&quot; to the Search Menu</P>
<P>&#9;Modifying the replace function so that it may do either a single replace or replace ALL.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>If you completed optional sections of the program, please document this fact in the &quot;Declarations&quot; section of your primary form.</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Product Delivery Requirements</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This project should follow the naming convention for variables and objects.  This project will be graded based on the requirements listed in the &quot;Program Requirements&quot; section of the syllabus.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Please be prepared to hand in this assignment on a floppy disk on the due date listed in the syllabus.  A printed copy of the code is not required for this project.  Include on the your disk a copy of the source code in a subdirectory, and an executable version of the text editor in the same directory.</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>System Interface</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The interface should look something like the following.  </P>
<img src="np.gif" border=0>
<P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Other Requirements</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This program should consist of one form (possibly two) and at least one module.  The module (*.BAS file) should contain any code that can be considered common (accessing the common dialog, loading files, saving files, searching a text box for a specific string, etc.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P></FONT></BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
