<TITLE>Script Processing</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P ALIGN="CENTER">Script Processing Specifications</P>
<B><P><A HREF="scripcode.html">Code Samples</A></P>

<B><P>Introduction</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>This assignment looks very similar to the last.  It must have at least the following features from assignment the text processor assignment:</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>

<UL>

<UL>
<LI>New</LI>
<LI>File Open</LI>
<LI>File Save</LI>
<LI>Exit</LI>
<LI>Cut</LI>
<LI>Copy</LI>
<LI>Paste</LI>
<LI>Find</LI>
<LI>Replace All</LI></UL>
</UL>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>This represents the minimum.   Using the complete interface of the notepad assignment is acceptable.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Script Processing Description</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Script processing is much like running a batch file at a DOS prompt.  Each line of a test file will be interpreted as a command for the computer to execute.  To accomplish this, your program will parse each command into its components and execute the command.  </P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Menu Changes</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>You will make a copy of your notepad program and add additional menu options for the new scripting commands.  The menu system should have the items listed above and an additional &quot;Run&quot; menu.  The &quot;Run&quot; menu should have sub-menu options called: &quot;Clear Errors&quot; and &quot;Start.&quot;</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Clear Errors Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The &quot;Clear Errors&quot; menu option should clear the list box used to store errors or status messages (LSTBox.Clear).</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Start Menu Option</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The start menu option should begin processing the script displayed in the text edit area of the system.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Current Menu Changes</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The &quot;New&quot; option under the file menu should clear the &quot;error display area&quot; as well as the &quot;text edit area&quot;.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Interface Changes</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The text processor has a slightly different interface than the scripting program you are about to write.  The following sections itemize changes necessary to the interface to allow it to function in the script processor.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>New List Box</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The new interface requires a text edit area like before and a list box at the top of the screen for status messages from the script process.  Directly below the list box should be the multi-line text box you used in your notepad program.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Resize Event</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The Resize Event of the primary form may have to change.  If you coded the resize event to move your text box to the upper left position of the window, you will have to pass the left and top of the text box as the starting point for your move command instead of the hard-coded parameters used.   The resize event should resize the text box only not the list box.  See Figure 1 for a picture of the interface.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Text Box</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The text box in your notepad should have the &quot;ScrollBars&quot; property set to &quot;Vertical.&quot;  For this new program, the &quot;ScrollBars&quot; property should be set to &quot;Both.&quot;  This will ensure that a command will not  wrap an look line more than one line when the use is modifying scripts.</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Script Description</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The scripts your program will process will have one command per line and will be loaded in to the text edit area by your File, Open command.  Because each command is stored on one line, they will be separated by Carriage Return  and Line Feed characters (Chr$(13) &amp; Chr$(10)) or  VbCrLF constant).  Each command will have a name (described below) and a series of command line parameters.  The parameters will exist in the same order as described in this document.  The processing of the script must not be case sensitive.  All command line parameters will be divided by spaces Chr$(32).  Any parameter that has spaces as part of the data will be passed will have the parameter enclosed in double quotes (Chr$(34)).</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>For example, one command you will execute is the copy command.  This command has the syntax: Copy c:\file1.txt c:\file2.txt; where &quot;file1&quot; is the source file to copy and &quot;file2 is the file to copy to.  Your program will be able to divide the command up into its sections:  &quot;Copy&quot;, &quot;c:\file1.txt&quot;, and &quot;c:\file2.txt.&quot;  After this point your program will execute the VB internal command: FileCopy and pass it the appropriate parameters.  Later in this document you will find a list of all command that must be accepted and their format.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>When a command is processed, it should return any and status messages to the list box (as described below).</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Sample Script</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The following is a sample script that may be processed.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P></FONT>
<TABLE BORDER CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=7 WIDTH=523>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Command to be processed</B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<B><FONT SIZE=2><P>Description</B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>COPY C:\WINDOWS\WIN.INI A:\TEST.TXT </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Copy a file</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>SHELL NOTEPAD  A:\TEST.TXT</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Run the windows notepad and display the file A:\TEXT.TXT</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>SET MYVAR &quot;Hello world&quot;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Set the user-defined variable Myvar to equal Hello World.</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>DELETE A:\TEST.TXT</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Delete the file A:\TEST.TXT</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>ECHO File Deleted </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Display the text &quot;File Deleted&quot; to the status list box</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>ECHO %MYVAR</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Display the current value of Myvar to the status list box</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Set MYVAR 23</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Change the value of Myvar to 23</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH="52%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Echo %MyVAR</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="48%" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT SIZE=2><P>Display the current value of Myvar to the status list box</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Commands to be processed</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The following are commands that the script program should be able to interpret.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Copy</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The copy command should use the intrinsic Visual Basic command FileCopy to copy a file from a source to a destination.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The syntax of the command you will process should be: <B>COPY <I>SourceFile/Path DestinationFile/Path</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Parameters</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT SIZE=2><P>SourceFile/Path</B></I>&#9;&#9;The source file to be copied</P>
<B><I><P>DestinationFile/Path</B></I>&#9;The destination file to copy to</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>NOTE:  There are only two command line parameters and they are separated by a space (Chr$(32)).</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Delete</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The Delete command should be able to delete a file from the system. Using the &quot;Kill&quot; command.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The syntax of this command should be:  <B>DELETE <I>filename</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Parameters</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT SIZE=2><P>filename</B></I>&#9;&#9;The name / path to the file to be deleted.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Shell</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Shell should start another program under with windows environment.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The syntax of the shell command should be <B>SHELL <I>shellfile</I> &quot;<I>shellparameters</I>&quot;</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Parameters</P>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>shellfile&#9;&#9;&#9;The executable program that the command is to shell</P>
<P>&quot;shellparameters&quot;&#9;&#9;The parameters the shell program that needs to operate.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Set</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The set stores a value to a user-defined variable.  This is not like a normal VB variable.  To accomplish this task you will create a global two dimensional array of length 1,20 (Global MyArr(1,20) as string).  In this array you will store the name of the variable and the value of the variable.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>When changing a value for a variable, you program will first have to see if the variable already exists.  If it already exists, your program will change the value to the new one.  If the variable does not exist, a new variable will be added.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The syntax of the set command should be SET <B><I>VariableName NewValue</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Parameters</P>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>VariableName&#9;&#9;The name of the variable as defined by the user</P>
<P>NewValue&#9;&#9;The value to be stored.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Echo</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The echo command should add a line to your status list box that contains what ever the user has to display.   The user may ask for two types of things to display.  First, a message that contains just text; and second one of the user-defined variables created by the Set command.  If the first character of the parameters is a &quot;%&quot;, the user wishes to display one of the user-defined variables.  Otherwise, display the text succeeding the echo command to the list box as entered. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The syntax of the echo command should be: ECHO &quot;<B><I>stuff&quot; or %var .</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Parameters</P>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Stuff&#9;&#9;&#9;The stuff to display in the list box.</P>
<P>%var&#9;&#9;&#9;a variable to display</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Error Messages</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Errors and status messages should be reported to a list box on the screen.  This list box will contain a single line per command in the command window when the script is complete.</P>
</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Successful Commands</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>Successful commands should report the name of the command and then &quot;Completed!&quot; to the list window like the following example:</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Copy - Complete!</P>
</FONT><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>Command Errors</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>If a command has an error, the system should report an error message.. Certain error messages will be generated by your processing system; however, consideration should be taken for system errors by using the &quot;on error&quot; routines. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The system should report error messages when the use has entered incorrect command line parameters.  Specifically one of the following:</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<B><P>Parameter Missing!</B>&#9;The script program should report this error when a user has entered command where the number of parameters does not match the required number of parameters.</P>
<B><P>Error! &quot;Error Name&quot;</B>&#9;The system should report any system errors generated during the execution of the script using t his format. &quot;Error Name&quot; should be obtained from the &quot;Error$&quot; command in VB. </P>
<B><P>Too Many Parameters!</B>&#9;Your system should verify the number of parameters and ensure that they are correct before processing the command.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

</FONT><B><I><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>When A System Error Occurs</P>
</B></I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>When any system error happens, your program should report the error (in the format described above) and then continue with the next instruction in the script.  The script should not abort.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Sample Screen</P>
</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><P>The following is a sample screen for the system.  It does not necessarily have to look like this; however, it must contain the functionality of this screen and should conform to a standard user interface.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><img src="script.gif" border=0>P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=6><P>Sample Parsing Code</P>
</B></FONT>

<pre>
'Parsing Procedure
'
'This procedure is passed a source string and returns the text starting at the
'P_StartPosition character and before the first delimeter found.
'
'if something is found, P_FoundText will have the text in it, and P_StartPostion will be
'placed after the delimeter found
'
'if nothing is found, then P_FoundText will be empty and P_StartPostion will be the
'original starting postion.
'
Public Sub GetByDelimeter(ByVal P_SourceText As String, ByVal P_Delimeter As String, P_StartPosition As Long, P_FoundText As String)

    Dim NewPos As Long
    Dim Result As String

    'locate the first occurrence of the delimeter</P>
    NewPos = InStr(P_StartPosition, P_SourceText, P_Delimeter, 1)
    If NewPos &gt; 0 Then
        If NewPos = 1 Then  ' if the found position equals 1 there
          			    'is no command before the start position 
                            'and the end position

           P_FoundText = ""
        Else
           P_FoundText = Mid$(P_SourceText, P_StartPosition, NewPos - P_StartPosition)
        End If
        'move the new start position to the end of the delimeter found.
        P_StartPosition = NewPos + Len(P_Delimeter)
    Else
        P_FoundText = ""
    End If

End Sub
</PRE>
</BODY>
