<P>

<font size=2>
<b><center>
Professors at Baylor University Use Visual C++&reg; and Visual Basic&reg; to Give Students Valuable 
Experience in Solving "Real World" Design Problems</center>
</b>
<P>

April 1996
<P>

For students seeking jobs in the area of computer systems design, Baylor Univerity, in Waco, Texas, offers 
a course which recognizes the importance of both hardware and software. Using Microsoft Visual C++ 
and Microsoft Visual Basic in a laboratory-based course, students create functional solutions to well-
defined design problems. 
<P>

<b>Background</b><BR>

At Baylor University, EGR 4438 started as an advanced logic course. But with the need for practical 
experience solving real-world design problems, the class now concentrates on computer systems issues 
where both hardware and software are important elements. In the course, which emphasizes lab work, 
students are expected to design and integrate computer systems (hardware and software) that solve 
specific, real-world design problems.<P>

<b>Microsoft software adds to lab experiences</b><BR>

The goal of EGR 4438 is to teach students the principles of computer system design. Professor Steven 
Eisenbarth chose Microsoft Visual C++, Visual Basic, and Windows NT&reg; for the programming tools 
and development environment in the labs.
<P>

"I needed a stable environment for C/C++ to be used in the design of real-time and embedded computer 
systems," says Eisenbarth. "The target systems are embedded (Intel 386) systems which allow the software 
to be developed on a host system (Windows NT) and then easily transported to the target system for test 
and debugging."
<P>
Textbooks for the course include <u>BiCMOS/CMOS Systems Design</u> by Buchanan and 
<u>Definition of the Engineering Method</u> by Koen, but the focus of the class is definitely lab work. 
Products of lab and design projects constitute 60 percent of the course grade. Projects include designing, 
implementing, and testing a low-speed, shared-bus communications network and a distributed data 
acquisition system; and designing, prototyping, and testing an optical scanner. In these projects, students 
are able to choose which programming language (C/C++ or Visual Basic) suits their needs.<P>

<b>Students find success in real-world designs</b><BR>

With its emphasis on designing complete solutions, the class teaches students more than programming 
techniques or specifics about hardware issues. Project teams must consider system integration, packaging, 
design for testability and manufacturability. Projects are judged on the team's documentation and oral 
presentations, as well as the hardware and software the team has produced.
<P>

Success in class labs helps prepare students for successful job searches outside of college. "Companies 
such as Dell, Motorola, Texas Instruments, and AMD have hired these students," says Eisenbarth. "These 
jobs cover a wide range of positions from manufacturing to hardware and software systems design."
<P>

<blockquote><i>
"Microsoft's willingness to provide Visual C++ and Visual Basic for class/lab development made a 
considerable difference in the quality of the educational experience for my students"</i><p>
                     <blockquote><font size=1> 
                     Steven Eisenbarth, Professor<BR>
                      Computer Science<BR>
                      Baylor University</font></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
Internet Site:<BR>
<a href="http://www.baylor.edu">http://www.baylor.edu - campus</a><BR>
<a href="http://ecswww.baylor.edu">http://ecswww.baylor.edu - course</a>
<P>


