<HEAD>

<TITLE>Microsoft Academic Cooperative - Visual C++ helps Community College</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="ffffff" background="gifs/tileband.gif" link="333399" alink="333399" vlink="333399">
<basefont size=2>
<basefont face="arial, geneva">


	<table border=0 width=540>
<tr><td valign=top align=left nowrap colspan=6>

<a href="index.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/homebar.gif" ALT="Home" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"><a href="ResourceCenter.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButRC1.gif" ALT="Resource Center" ALIGN=BOTTOM  BORDER="0"></a><a href="ILG.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButILG2.gif" ALT="Instructional Grant Program" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="SearchPage.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButCnR3.gif" ALT="Curriculum &amp; Reference Searches" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="HardWare.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButHard4.gif" ALT="Hardware Opportunities" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="ProductPricing.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButPap5.gif" ALT="Products &amp; Academic Pricing" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a>
</td></tr>


		<tr>
		<td align=left width="115">
<IMG SRC="gifs/blank.gif" ALT="empty space" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="2" 
BORDER="0">
		</td>
		<td align=left valign=top>
<BR>

<P>

<font size=2>
<b><center>
Using Microsoft&reg; Visual C++&reg; Helps a Struggling Community College Offer
"Real-World" Development Tools to Students</center>

</b>
<P>

April 1996

<P>

At North Idaho College in Coeur d'Alene, CS 150 offers an introduction to the field of computer science 
using Microsoft Visual C++  and Microsoft Windows&reg; 95. To help students understand the software 
development process, at least one program assignment is a team project in which the class creates a useful 
piece of software for the campus or a local business.

<P>

<b>Background</b><BR>

At North Idaho College, administrators have revised several computer science courses to keep up with 
existing technology demands. Courses are now taught with Microsoft products such as Microsoft 
Windows 95, Visual Basic&reg;, and Visual C++.
<P>

<b>Choosing Microsoft Software</b><BR>

Professor David Mann uses Microsoft Visual C++ and Microsoft Windows 95 in his Computer Science 
150 course, an introduction to the field of computer science that includes computer organization, 
algorithmic problem solving, and structured program design. The class is a requirement for all Computer 
Science majors at NIC, and students must also take a concurrent CS-150 lab with the course.

<P>

CS-150 provides computer science students with an opportunity to gain experience and confidence to 
prepare them for a rigorous Data Structures/ Algorithms class. Required reading for the course includes 
<u>The Object Concept</u>, by Decker and Hirshfield, as well as the accompanying lab manual. 

<P>
Mann chose Microsoft programming languages in part because they are used to develop applications in 
businesses as well as in the academic sphere. In addition, evaluation of various software packages 
indicated that Microsoft programming tools were industry standards -- important for preparing students 
for life past college halls. "We felt that if the languages were understandable for our beginning students, 
then the students would be better off to learn these languages as opposed to some teaching language that 
they would never see again," says Mann.

<P>

<b>Helping Students Learn the Development Process</b><BR>

During the first month of the course, Mann has his students use Visual C++ to code both a half adder and 
a full adder inside the machine. Students then move to a more complicated programming project -- 
currently, CS-150 students are creating a UPS-style package tracker simulation.

<P>

At least one program assignment is a class project where students create a useful (but not too large) piece 
of software for the campus or a local business. Students are assigned to teams and have an opportunity to 
experience what it's like to develop software applications in the "real world" plus interact with each other 
on the development team.

<P>
Next fall, Mann plans on assigning a design problem that will provide a much-needed solution for the 
campus. CS-150 students will use Visual C++ to write a package for NIC administrators to manage and 
track faculty assignments to committees -- plus the terms of the assignments. 


<blockquote><i>
"It means a great deal to me and this department to have some direct support from the industry as we try 
to keep current in a rapidly changing field."</i><p>
                     <blockquote><font size=1> 
                     Dave Mann, Professor<BR>                  
            		 Computer Science<BR>
                     North Idaho College</font></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
Internet Site:<BR>
<a href=" http://selkirk.csrv.nidc.edu"> http://selkirk.csrv.nidc.edu</a>

<P>


