<HEAD>

<TITLE>Microsoft Academic Cooperative - Visual C++ used to Excite Students</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="ffffff" background="gifs/tileband.gif" link="333399" alink="333399" vlink="333399">
<basefont size=2>
<basefont face="arial, geneva">


	<table border=0 width=540>
<tr><td valign=top align=left nowrap colspan=6>

<a href="index.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/homebar.gif" ALT="Home" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"><a href="ResourceCenter.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButRC1.gif" ALT="Resource Center" ALIGN=BOTTOM  BORDER="0"></a><a href="ILG.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButILG2.gif" ALT="Instructional Grant Program" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="SearchPage.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButCnR3.gif" ALT="Curriculum &amp; Reference Searches" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="HardWare.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButHard4.gif" ALT="Hardware Opportunities" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="ProductPricing.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButPap5.gif" ALT="Products &amp; Academic Pricing" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a>
</td></tr>

		<tr>
		<td align=left width="115">
<IMG SRC="gifs/blank.gif" ALT="empty space" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="2" 
BORDER="0">
		</td>
		<td align=left valign=top>
<BR>


<P>

<font size=2>
<b><center>
Professors at Illinois Institute of Technology Use Visual C++&reg;
and "Real-World" Solutions to Get Students Excited About Computer Science</center>

</b>
<P>

April 1996
<P>

At Illinois Institute of Technology (IIT) in Chicago, Illinois, professors are using Microsoft&reg; Visual 
C++  in a new laboratory-based computer science curriculum. Students use Visual C++ to create 
functional solutions to well-defined design problems. They then attend review meetings where they 
receive constructive feedback on their project designs, preliminary programs, and final projects. 
<P>

<b>Background</b><BR>

Seven years ago, IIT administrators asked themselves a difficult question: "What are we doing to excite 
students about computer science?" As a result, professors changed the way they taught their computer 
science courses -- creating a structure where students are challenged to be active, creative partners in the 
learning process, and providing ample support for their creative endeavors. 
<P>

<b>Giving constructive feedback</b><BR>

Associate Professor James Roberge' uses Visual C++ to teach a Data Structures and Algorithms class, a 
requirement for all CS majors. The goal of the course is for students to learn how to implement and apply 
the essential data structures used in computer science, with particular emphasis on object-oriented 
design/programming (OOD/OOP). 
<P>

Textbooks for the course include <u>Introduction to Programming in C++</u>: A Laboratory Course, by 
Roberge' and Smith, and C++: How to Program, by Deitel and Deitel.
<P>
A required, weekly hands-on lab complements the lectures. Professor Roberge' provides assignments in 
Visual C++ where students work with a lab instructor and their peers to eliminate any flaws in their 
designs. "Rather than simply returning graded homework, we give students support as they solve problems 
for themselves," says Roberge'. "The resulting self-confidence and sense of mastery is readily apparent, 
both to them and to us."
<P>

<b>Visual C++ -- the tool of choice</b><BR>

Because the interface is so easy to learn, Roberge' chose Visual C++ as the compiler of choice to teach 
students who are a mix of undergraduates and upper division students from other majors. "We're among 
the first programs to base our introductory courses on object-oriented programming in C++," says 
Roberge'.
<P>

Another reason for the choice is the Microsoft Foundation Class Library (MFC). At the introductory level, 
MFC makes it easy for CS professors to develop application frameworks for student programming 
projects. For more advanced courses, MFC vividly shows the ease with which powerful software products 
can be developed using contemporary tools and software development technologies.

<P>
Changing the way the school taught computer science has benefited students and faculty alike. Evidence 
of the success is that area corporations often demand IIT students for their summer internships and co-op 
positions. "Most important," adds Roberge', "our students are noticeably more excited about computer 
science as a profession."
<P>

<blockquote><i>
"Visual C++ and MFC make it easy to create lab exercises that are practical, pedagogically sound, and 
which focus on novel applications -- rather than simply reconstituted exercises that have survived since 
the 'Dawn of the Computer Age'."</i><p>
                     <blockquote><font size=1> 
                     James Roberge', Associate Chair<BR>
                      Dept. of Computer Science & Applied Mathematics<BR>
                      Illinois Institute of Technology</font></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
Internet Site:<BR>
<a href="http://www.csam.iit.edu/~cs331">http://www.csam.iit.edu/~cs331</a>

<P>


