<HEAD>

<TITLE>Microsoft Academic Cooperative - Visual Basic in use at Moorpark College</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="ffffff" background="gifs/tileband.gif" link="333399" alink="333399" vlink="333399">
<basefont size=2>
<basefont face="arial, geneva">


	<table border=0 width=540>
<tr><td valign=top align=left nowrap colspan=6>

<a href="index.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/homebar.gif" ALT="Home" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"><a href="ResourceCenter.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButRC1.gif" ALT="Resource Center" ALIGN=BOTTOM  BORDER="0"></a><a href="ILG.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButILG2.gif" ALT="Instructional Grant Program" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="SearchPage.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButCnR3.gif" ALT="Curriculum &amp; Reference Searches" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="HardWare.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButHard4.gif" ALT="Hardware Opportunities" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="ProductPricing.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButPap5.gif" ALT="Products &amp; Academic Pricing" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a>
</td></tr>

		<tr>
		<td align=left width="115">
<IMG SRC="gifs/blank.gif" ALT="empty space" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="2" 
BORDER="0">
		</td>
		<td align=left valign=top>
<BR>


<P>

<font size=2>
<b><center>
Computer Science Students at Moorpark College in California Use Visual Basic&reg; to Create Practical 
Applications for the Real World</center>

</b>
<P>
May 1996

<P>

At Moorpark College in Moorpark, California, the computer science faculty stresses hands-on learning, so 
CIS-3B, Advanced Visual Basic, is taught in the computer lab instead of in a classroom. For the final 
programming assignment, students must design and develop an application that could be sold 
commercially in either a vertical or a horizontal market. 
<P>

<b>Background</b><BR>

When Professor Guy Campbell at Moorpark College designed his Visual Basic courses, he "built them 
from the ground up." Originally a C/C++ programmer, Professor Campbell became proficient in the 
Microsoft&reg; Visual Basic programming system to create more than 30 projects for classes that range 
from beginning to advanced.
<P>
"Advanced Visual Basic is a very hands-on course," explained Professor Campbell. "Because it is taught 
in the school's computer lab, students spend over two-thirds of their class time using Visual Basic."
<P>

<b>High-level programming topics</b><BR>

CIS-3B is required for all computer science majors at Moorpark. Students must have previous Visual 
Basic programming experience to enroll in the course.
<P>

The CIS-3B syllabus includes creating, accessing, organizing, and processing databases with Visual Basic 
and linking and embedding objects from OLE server applications, plus creating both OLE- and Visual 
Basic-based applications.
<P>
Required textbooks include <u>Essential Visual Basic 4</u>, by Mark Steven Heyman, and <u>The 
Visual Guide to Visual Basic 4.0 for Windows</u>, by Richard Mansfield. Professor Campbell also 
recommends that his students get Microsoft Visual Basic version 4.0, Professional Edition, so that they 
can complete programming assignments at home.
<P>

<b>Students get real with Visual Basic</b><BR>

To help the class understand real-world program development, each student must design and code a 
commercially viable application.
<P>

One student used Visual Basic to create a home data center in which everyone in the family could write 
notes to the others, keep track of his or her favorite television shows and movies, and even maintain 
private diaries that were password protected.

<P>
Another student, an insurance adjuster, used the final programming project to streamline his business. He 
created a proprietary Visual Basic-based application to enter and maintain his clients' insurance 
adjustments (such as for earthquake damage) that were previously done only on paper.
<P>
In almost every case, the class's final projects have exceeded Professor Campbell's expectations. "I'm quite 
proud," he said, "that some of my students' ideas do become viable products."
<P>

<blockquote><i>
"With Visual Basic, students don't have to keep so much in their heads until the program compiles -- they 
can see how the program will run as they code. This makes it easy for them to construct programs that run 
right the first time around."</i><p>
                     <blockquote><font size=1> 
                     Guy Campbell, Professor<BR>
                     Computer Information Science<BR>
                     Moorpark College</font></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
Internet Site:<BR>
<a href="http://www.vcccd.cc.ca.us/~gcampbell/">http://www.vcccd.cc.ca.us/~gcampbell/</a>

<P>


