<HEAD>

<TITLE>Microsoft Academic Cooperative - Visual C++ in use at Northeast Louisiana University</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="ffffff" background="gifs/tileband.gif" link="333399" alink="333399" vlink="333399">
<basefont size=2>
<basefont face="arial, geneva">


	<table border=0 width=540>
<tr><td valign=top align=left nowrap colspan=6>

<a href="index.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/homebar.gif" ALT="Home" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"><a href="ResourceCenter.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButRC1.gif" ALT="Resource Center" ALIGN=BOTTOM  BORDER="0"></a><a href="ILG.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButILG2.gif" ALT="Instructional Grant Program" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="SearchPage.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButCnR3.gif" ALT="Curriculum &amp; Reference Searches" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="HardWare.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButHard4.gif" ALT="Hardware Opportunities" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a><a href="ProductPricing.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/ButPap5.gif" ALT="Products &amp; Academic Pricing" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0"></a>
</td></tr>

		<tr>
		<td align=left width="115">
<IMG SRC="gifs/blank.gif" ALT="empty space" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="2" 
BORDER="0">
		</td>
		<td align=left valign=top>
<BR>

<P>

<font size=2>
<b><center>
Professors at Northeast Louisiana University Find Visual C++&reg; Flexible Enough to Use in Computer 
Classes That Range from Beginning to Advanced</center>
</b>
<P>
May 1996

<P>
At Northeast Louisiana University in Monroe, computer science students progress through a sequence of 
courses to learn to program in Microsoft&reg; Visual C++. Because Visual C++ presents an intuitive 
development environment, professors have begun to teach object-oriented programming in lower-level 
courses. An advanced class -- CSCI 498 -- now focuses on object-oriented design.
<P>

<b>Background</b><BR>

When CSCI faculty at Northeast Louisiana University designed their curriculum, they agreed that the 
Visual C++ development system should be the primary language for computer science majors. 
<P>
The faculty adapted three required classes from earlier introductory material that had been taught in 
Pascal before the department switched to Visual C++. They then created a fourth course, CSCI 498, 
Object Oriented Programming, as an elective. CSCI 498 teaches object-oriented design to students who 
have been introduced to the concept in the lower-level courses.

<P>

<b>Learning object-oriented design </b><BR>

CSCI 498 was originally intended to teach students object-oriented programming. However, according to 
Professor Ron Classen, "As we include more object-oriented programming in the lower-level courses, 
CSCI 498 is evolving into an OO design course." The class learns methods of identifying classes and 
objects, the process and annotation for object-oriented design, and case studies of object-oriented systems.
<P>

Using Visual C++, students also develop object-oriented software, including a bank simulation and several 
programs for the Windows&reg; operating system that utilize the Microsoft Foundation Class Library.
<P>
<u>C++ Inside and Out</u>, by Bruce C. Eckel, and <u>The C++ Programming Language, Second 
Edition</u>, by Bjarne Stroustrup, are required textbooks for the course.
<P>

<b>Visual C++ language for all classes</b><BR>

Faculty members use Visual C++ as a programming environment in courses that range from basic to 
complex. According to Professor Classen, Visual C++ "allows development of simple applications so that 
beginning students do not have to know a great deal about the Microsoft Windows environment and 
Windows classes. On the other hand," he added, "there are professional-level capabilities -- such as the 
Microsoft Foundation Class Library, the menu editor, and the icon editor -- that are useful for students in 
the more advanced courses." 
<P>

Students in CSCI 498 enjoy learning object-oriented design using Visual C++. The reason? They can 
concentrate on interface design without having to handle vast amounts of code to implement it. According 
to Professor Classen, using Visual C++ helps his computer science students "become proficient at 
programming using an industrial-strength software development tool."
<P>

<blockquote><i>
"Visual C++ provides an excellent development environment. It allows programming of simple, MS-
DOS&reg;-type applications so that beginning students do not have to know a great deal about the 
Windows environment."</i><p>
                     <blockquote><font size=1> 
                     Ron Classen, Professor<BR>
                     Computer Science<BR>
                     Northeast Louisiana University</font></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
Internet Site:<BR>
<a href="http://www.nlu.edu">http://www.nlu.edu (campus)</a><BR>
<a 
href="http://hurricane.net2.nlu.edu/~youngbld/csci.html">http://hurricane.net2.nlu.edu/~youngbld/csci.ht
ml (course)</a>

<P>


