<BR>

<P>

<font size=2>
<b><center>
Students in a Database Design Course at the University of Illinois Discover Their Skills Translate into 
Increased Job Opportunities</center>
</b>
<P>
May 1996

<P>
At the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, CS 411 students use the Microsoft&reg; Visual 
C++&reg; development system to implement real-world database design projects. Exposure to database 
management and advanced programming tools gives these students a head start on their careers. Many 
receive job offers from industry leaders such as Hewlett-Packard, AT&T, and Informix.
<P>

<b>Background</b><BR>

CS 411, Design of Database Management Systems, is a graduate-level computer science course at the 
University of Illinois. In the class, Professor Sharod Mehrotra teaches in-depth theory and database 
management implementation.
<P>
CS 411 is an elective for computer science majors at the college. A prerequisite course, CS 311, Database 
Systems, focuses on beginning-level database issues. 

<P>
Required reading includes <u>Optimized 2-Safe Approach</u>, by S. Mehrotra, plus a wide variety of 
research papers and conference proceedings on database topics.
<P>

<b>Microsoft products are first choice</b><BR>

The computer science faculty at UIUC chose Microsoft products to facilitate class projects. Students get 
hands-on experience with Microsoft Access, Visual C++, Microsoft SQL ServerTM, the Microsoft 
PowerPoint&reg; presentation graphics program, and the Windows NT&reg; operating system. "The main 
reasons for using Microsoft products are the students' desire to learn more about PC computing 
environments, the ease of use of [the] software, and its availability," said Professor Mehrotra. 
<P>

Class assignments and a project report represent 25 percent of a student's grade. Some of the projects are 
quite advanced, requiring students to use several software products. In one project, students implemented 
a workflow management system, which they developed on top of SQL Server. In another project, students 
designed a prototype multimedia retrieval system. 

<P>

<b>Experience leads to job offers</b><BR>

Because of their advanced knowledge of Microsoft tools and database management, students in CS 411 
receive job offers from leaders in the industry. Potential employers -- such as AT&T, UniSQL, Hewlett-
Packard, and the Army Research Labs -- post openings on the course's Internet home page and offer 
positions ranging from summer internships to permanent, full-time work. Informix (in Menlo Park, 
California) hopes to make offers to 40 percent of the department's graduates. 
<P>

According to Professor Mehrotra, taking CS 411 allows his students to choose from a variety of careers 
when they graduate. "Experience with database products helps them get database design jobs," he said. 
"And by understanding data management and implementation issues, students are better prepared to 
succeed in system engineering related jobs.
<P>

<blockquote><i>
"Online help and visual, user-friendly interfaces make it easy for students to learn Microsoft development 
products such as Visual C++." </i><p>
                     <blockquote><font size=1> 
                     Sharad Mehrotra, Professor<BR>
                     Computer Science<BR>
                     University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</font></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
